ase\\MattGanzak\\HeygenWorkflowLesson\\sprint_setup_guide.docx.txt:765:TikTok: 7:30 AM, 12:00 PM, 7:00 PM\r\nC:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\docs\\KnowledgeBase\\MattGanzak\\HeygenWorkflowLesson\\sprint_setup_guide.docx.txt:766:Instagram Reels: 9:30 AM, 1:00 PM\r\nC:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\docs\\KnowledgeBase\\MattGanzak\\HeygenWorkflowLesson\\sprint_setup_guide.docx.txt:767:YouTube Shorts: 1:00 PM\r\nC:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\docs\\KnowledgeBase\\MattGanzak\\HeygenWorkflowLesson\\sprint_setup_guide.docx.txt:897:12:00 PM\r\nC:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\docs\\KnowledgeBase\\MattGanzak\\HeygenWorkflowLesson\\transcription.txt:1:automation with Hey Jen, uh, step-by-step on how to create content. If you're creating content like I do on social media, if you just want like talking head type content, uh, this is exactly how to do it and automate it with open claw, uh, in the last video talking about UGC, that's more for, if you want like a model created or somebody like that, then you could create that with cling or VO three, et cetera. So I still want to do that video, but I want to do this one to talk about like talking head videos and how to program that. So let's go through step-by-step how this is going to work. So again, I'm not going to read through everything, but I'll give you access to this below. So you're going to need HeyGen, 11 Labs. And I'll talk about the breakdown of HeyGen and 11 Labs because HeyGen will generate voice for you based upon what you've already given it. But the downside is the quality might not be as good. So you can do it without 11 Labs or you can do it with 11 Labs. So definitely test it both ways. Costs will go up a little bit if you're generating the audio and then feeding the audio. into HeyGen and then it's syncing the mouth and blah, blah, blah, blah, blah. If you want to auto schedule, you can use buffer. So I'll give you a walkthrough on that, on how we can schedule buffer. And if you want to put this into Google Docs, you could do that. I'll walk through that a little bit. And then I have Slack. Slack is mine, but you don't necessarily need that. But I want an update on how things are going on. So it would just be whichever channel you're using to communicate with your bot. Cool? Cool. All right. So we're training assets. So you need at least 10 to 20, uh, 10 seconds to 20 minutes worth of continuous uncut recording. So this is where we start training the avatar. I know it says we need at least 20 seconds, but the more you feed it, the better. And also when you're creating that video, like don't make any like quick head movements and don't be blinking like crazy because it will mess things up. So when I record and I'm making these, I'm trying to stay perfectly like I'm doing it right now. I'm trying to stay perfectly still talking to you and trying to keep my eyes open as much as possible. I know I just blinked but try to keep your eyes open as much as possible as you're talking about it. Don make too many facial expressions because it won really render correctly Like be kind of robotic in a sense So I mean it kind of sucks but you know that where we at Hopefully in the next three to six months like this gets better and better And I have been using HeyGen for like six months now and it has gotten better. So I will say that. So I'm just giving you some points. Cool. All right. So moving through. So now we're training the audio, talking about training the audio. Now we're going to start setting up where to set files and so forth. I'm going to give you some prompts here. So here's a prompt on how to set up this clones, you know, setup agent, like call it whatever you want and you can plug this in. So when you set this up, you're going to want to use a better reasoning model like Sonnet and, uh, you know, set this up, um, you know, using your HeyGen key. And if it's an environment, then you let it know it's in the environment. Um, uh, so forth. So yeah, I mean, you walk through and you set it up so you can go through that process and change it as you need. Cool. So that'll set it up and then you'll start setting up your job tasks and, and, you know, formatting on how that's going to look. And you have your flow here. This is the status flow, scripted voice, uh, so forth. So you can start, you know, training your model on this skill that we're creating in creating this type of content. Right. Uh, so the intake now, if you're doing, uh, Google sheets, uh, or Google docs or whatever, uh, you can set it up here and you can have everything like automated inside of Google sheets. You can go that route again. I don't like that extra layer that I don't need. So I'll just put it in a CSV and just keep it locally for me. But again, for you, if you need to do Google Sheets, you can go the route of Google Sheets. Otherwise, just keep it locally in a CSV to, you know, keep things super simple for you. Cool. So rolling through. So we're going to create the script writer. So here's where we're teaching it how to write hooks. You know, you're opening a line, how to script, how to write, how to do those things. So this will train it on how to do that. And that's a prompt step by step on how to write a hook, right? And, you know, here's a good hook example, et cetera. You can change that based upon what you need. Like if you're writing something like this in and you're training your agent based upon AI and so forth and cutting costs and specifically, that's kind of going to train it more to that. So you going to want to train it more to like if you running a day spa or something like that you going to want to train it to the specific of what that business is and give it a good example so you training it and having it understand Now we gonna create the voice agent So I'm using Haiku for this. So you can create the voice agent this way. Again, you can have HeyGen do it for you or you could feed it in audio and that's kind of what we're talking about here. You could feed it in audio and then it's gonna sync your avatar up to the audio of the video that is being uploaded to HeyGen. So this is the way that we're gonna do it. And so we're going to feed in via API and it's going to create it for you. Again, I did this for our training and we did it, uh, you know, pretty granularly. So like, uh, we're doing it in the hospital software. So if, you know, nurse Smith is messing up, um, you know, how to, you know, read the charts correctly or whatever, uh, we will automatically push that into nurse Smith and, um, the doctor will say, you know, nurse, uh, you know, there are a couple of things that we need to talk about, et cetera. So we did it so granularly that we can create videos like that. So I've used the API to do this. And therefore, I know we can do this in Opiclaw like really easily because it has access to the same APIs. So it's just giving you that transparency on that. Create your avatar video agent. So you're going to set it up this way. This is how it's going to generate, you know, that agent to go out and use the audio and so forth to then go and start rendering and, you know, creating that. And then you'll plug in your key. If it's an environment, then, you know, you'll use whatever the environment like session is for that API key there. And that'll plug in and boom, done. So give it some rules, give it some understanding of what it needs to do. And then this is the caption content. Again, haiku for this. And you can set it on that schedule and then you can run it for the captions. So you can have the captions add in. Captions will be automatically added on the video because who wants to do that? And it'll walk through and create the exact captions. And it should look good. It should work. But again, test it a few times. if you need to tweak it and so forth, you can tweak it and do what you need. Run it through your QA agent. So you'll set up this QA agent and then you'll have a pass, fail, flag, et cetera. And then you can have the QA agent let you know in your messenger service when something hits a problem and then it update you and let you know in that process Publisher agent So again if you want to do this and you want to automate it I would use something like Buffer because Buffer has an approved API into all these platforms. So I would use something like Buffer for auto scheduling. So I kind of give you the API call for that. So you can schedule that in. It'll write the caption. It'll write the description and all of that. But again, you might want to double check it and make sure it's working and then tweak it as needed as you go from there. You can create this analytics agent and then using Sonnet for this, running a schedule, and then it's just kind of tracking everything that's going on. So you can just track it through there and kind of understand what's going on. Again, I use Slack, so I could use a webhook to shoot me an update or whatever via that to let me know like, hey, this is going on and so forth. So yeah, this is a full breakdown of how to do it, how to set it up, everything that I do in breaking this down. And again, I program this like manually, the old way, but this is a way to do it in OpenClaw to have it be your orchestrator to do this task automatically. So I wanna make this video, post it up, give you access to this doc, and hopefully this is helpful. And let me know in the wins, if you get this set up and you get it automated and get it running, fantastic. Like I wanna hear in the wins about it. So cool. All right, I'm gonna do another video. I said I was gonna do the other video on UGC for VO3 or Kling. I haven't decided which one yet, but like, you know, my wife owns a business and she hates making content and I wanna have content of like models like doing content, talking about her product. So I'm trying to figure out how to get that to work for her business so I can write it autonomously for her business. So she can always have fresh content, but that would be Kling and VO3 to make models that would be talking about your product and so forth. This is more like you talking about the product. So you are authenticating that you're authorizing to say, yes, you can use my likeness in this video. You'll set up HeyGen, you'll do all of that. And then you can automate it based upon that model, that avatar that HeyGen creates. it will make videos over and over and over again with that exact setup. So this is exactly how to do it. All right, guys. See you on the next one.\r\nC:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\docs\\KnowledgeBase\\MattGanzak\\InstallingSkillsLesson\\openclaw-skills-security-guide.docx.pdf:40:?x?Ht?u?R??ae?j\\[rY?q?3a?::*?z/Q???d?H?lYKKX??{m8?Cl*\t/??A?????s#/?????q?`?K?su??eJn?KS?|??J??????_?k???5s??h?????q???@?????@=\"???6T?m?g?c??????*?G%$???X=9n'?[??a??k??sp?7??97?j8*?h?T#-ex?t?????X??b???>?0??????*?WVC??n??#????h,K??,\tiZ1K???#?U?4?C???mM{x??+??O??3?a?U???{m??x?O?�a7?]?W?%S?5????k????_?'?ysX?#g7;y?Ps?;?jq\\]???(?\\??m?<,??S??!?#?????]??-??^\\???W??WW?g?MM?;?8.:?'1{2??b?=????TZ??w9??B?:??PM?/??!m?\r\nC:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\docs\\KnowledgeBase\\MattGanzak\\InstallingSkillsLesson\\openclaw-skills-security-guide.docx.pdf:176:?e??r????????t?pm?r@)?o?o???X?Q?? o9?T????? VGf???*gx?C?j?IU???|??o?Y?j9v?h???F???J???t??????z?j??g$??m~?{E?x?_??[-\r\nC:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\docs\\KnowledgeBase\\MattGanzak\\InstallingSkillsLesson\\openclaw-skills-security-guide.docx.pdf:443:(???=#?(?:??:?\tX???pm??6?c!??;? ??????C?[??z?+]???\r\nC:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\docs\\KnowledgeBase\\MattGanzak\\InstallingSkillsLesson\\openclaw-skills-security-guide.docx.pdf:444:y(?d???J????7?g??D8????s??~s??S{OPM+Mx^??cS