{"type":"message","id":"2e7773c4","parentId":"76022f28","timestamp":"2026-03-30T14:51:01.515Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_yuXoFJgiC7RQrTyaCkEQzKfe|fc_0047bd771936d8e20169ca8dd5228c8195af230f6df44b6034","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"(no output)"}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":248,"aggregated":"","cwd":"C:\\Users\\User-OEM\\.openclaw\\workspace"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1774882261369}}
{"type":"message","id":"7d6a4cba","parentId":"2e7773c4","timestamp":"2026-03-30T14:51:01.636Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_9b1K14aywe4vckkaUqHKnB9e|fc_0047bd771936d8e20169ca8dd5229c8195a93713dfa87f02ef","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# Production Manager — Arquitectura e Especificação\n\n_Documento vivo. Actualizado conforme a arquitectura evolui._\n\n_Última actualização: 28 Mar 2026_\n\n---\n\n## Papel\n\nO Production Manager (PM) é o Nível 2 da hierarquia — o gerente operacional. Recebe ordens do Tobias (CEO) ou roda em cron, analisa a planilha PUB no Google Sheets, calcula a urgência de cada canal, e gera um artefacto JSON (job) para o Video Orchestrator executar.\n\n### O que FAZ\n- Analisa a planilha PUB para determinar qual canal precisa de vídeo mais urgentemente\n- Calcula runway (dias até ficar sem conteúdo) por canal\n- Gera artefactos JSON com todas as configs necessárias para produção\n- Respeita overrides dinâmicos do Lucca (via Tobias)\n- Reporta ao Tobias sobre estado da produção\n- Envia o job para o **Video Orchestrator** (ver doc 11)\n\n### O que NÃO FAZ\n- Não fala directamente com o Lucca (isso é o Tobias)\n- Não decide estratégia (isso é o Tobias)\n- Não executa tarefas de produção (isso são os operadores nos setores)\n- Não orquestra o pipeline de produção (isso é o Video Orchestrator)\n- Não toma decisões criativas\n\n---\n\n## Relação com o Video Orchestrator\n\nO PM decide **O QUE** produzir. O Video Orchestrator gere **COMO** produzir.\n\n```\nPM: \"C003 FRA precisa de vídeo, runway 1 dia\" → gera job JSON\n                    |\nVideo Orchestrator: recebe job → cria directório → busca script\n                    → orquestra S1→S2→...→S10\n                    → reporta status ao Tobias e Lucca\n```\n\nO Video Orchestrator é documentado em `docs/11_VIDEO_ORCHESTRATOR.md`.\n\n---\n\n## Modelo\n\n**Qwen 3.5 9B** via Ollama (local, $0). Lógica estruturada — não precisa de modelo pesado.\n\n---\n\n## Fonte de Dados: Planilha PUB\n\n**Sheet ID**: `1XL6VhOTVVMmfGNqPyJra2T8KjfFbtJ1o16OZkytvCPc`\n**Tab**: PUB\n**Acesso**: Google Sheets API via service account\n\n### Colunas Relevantes\n\n| Coluna | Header | Significado |\n|--------|--------|-------------|\n| B | ULT PUB | Data do último vídeo já programado no YouTube Studio (upload feito, scheduled) |\n| F | PROGRAMAR | Vídeos produzidos mas ainda não uploaded/scheduled no YouTube |\n| J | PROD | Se a produção está activa para este canal (SIM/NÃO) |\n| O | SCRIPTS | Scripts disponíveis no formato \"usados/total\" (ex: \"38/57\") |\n\n### Canais Activos (PROD=SIM)\n\n| Linhas PUB | Account | Idiomas | Qtd |\n|------------|---------|---------|-----|\n| 6-8 | 001 | fr, de, pt | 3 |\n| 9-13 | 002 | en, ko, ja, es, pt | 5 |\n| 14-21 | 003 | en, pt, fr, ko, de, it, es, ja | 8 |\n| 22-28 | 004 | en, es, it, fr, pt, ko, ja | 7 |\n| 29-39 | 005 | en, it, de, ko, ru, tr, pl, pt, ja, fr, es | 11 |\n| 40 | 006 | pt | 1 |\n| 42-45 | 008 | en, es, it, pt | 4 |\n| **Total** | **7 accounts** | | **39 canais** |\n\n---\n\n## Lógica de Decisão\n\n### Filtro Eliminatório\n\n1. `PROD = SIM` (coluna J)\n2. Scripts restantes > 0 (coluna O: se \"38/57\", sobram 19; se \"57/57\", sobram 0 → não produz)\n\n### Cálculo de Runway\n\n```\nrunway = PROGRAMAR (col F) + dias_ate_ultimo_programado(ULT_PUB - hoje)\n```\n\n- **ULT PUB** (col B) = data do último vídeo programado no YouTube Studio\n- **PROGRAMAR** (col F) = vídeos prontos mas ainda não scheduled\n- **Runway** = quantos dias o canal aguenta antes de ficar sem conteúdo\n\n#### Exemplos (supondo hoje = 26/03/2026)\n\n| Canal | ULT PUB | PROGRAMAR | Cálculo | Runway | Status |\n|-------|---------|-----------|---------|--------|--------|\n| C005 ING | 25/03 | 0 | 0 + (-1) | **-1** | CRÍTICO (já sem vídeos) |\n| C003 FRA | 27/03 | 0 | 0 + 1 | **1** | URGENTE |\n| C002 ESP | 27/03 | 1 | 1 + 1 | **2** | OK |\n| C005 COR | 27/03 | 3 | 3 + 1 | **4** | Tranquilo |\n\n### Prioridade (ordem)\n\n1. **Override dinâmico do Lucca** — via Tobias. Sobrepõe tudo.\n   - Exemplos: \"só conta 03 hoje\", \"prioriza 05 en e 03 fr\", \"só contas monetizadas\"\n   - Pode durar horas, dias, ou até nova ordem\n2. **Menor runway** — canal com menos dias até ficar sem conteúdo\n3. Em caso de empate: menor número de account (001 antes de 005)\n\n---\n\n## Trigger\n\n### Fase 1 (actual)\nTobias acciona o PM de duas formas:\n- **\"Escolhe um vídeo para produzir\"** → PM analisa PUB, calcula runways, decide\n- **\"Produz conta 003 francês\"** → PM executa ordem directa sem calcular\n\n### Fase 2 (futuro)\nCron job periódico — PM verifica PUB automaticamente e decide.\n\n---\n\n## Output: Artefacto JSON (Job)\n\nQuando o PM decide qual canal produzir, gera um artefacto com tudo que o Video Orchestrator precisa:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"job_id\": \"2026-03-26_003_fr_001\",\n  \"account\": \"003\",\n  \"language\": \"fr\",\n  \"channel_name\": \"C003 FRA\",\n  \"sheet_scripts_id\": \"1H-9M1V_COUWOu9TLPLB2R41z5XMrzdh6mhXxo-XY6n8\",\n  \"sheet_scripts_name\": \"Pagina1\",\n  \"sheet_tracking_id\": \"1fnA5QeiNDTzakQW8gtVovLnlAofMWGDfGHGmm6ZX3TE\",\n  \"drive_folder_id\": \"17FSjYxw3NEOuKHqA3abE0IJAN6V9u_H7\",\n  \"v3_config\": \"accounts/003_wwii_photography/configs/003-fr.yaml\",\n  \"channel_url\": \"https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCzfZRuRHSp6erCwzuhjywFw\",\n  \"runway_days\": 1,\n  \"reason\": \"Runway 1 dia (ULT PUB 27/03, PROGRAMAR 0)\",\n  \"priority_override\": null,\n  \"created_at\": \"2026-03-26T14:30:00\"\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n## Configs\n\n### Localização\n```\nauto_content_factory/accounts/\n├── registry.yaml              <- Índice mestre\n├── 001/\n│   ├── fr.yaml, de.yaml, pt.yaml\n├── 002/\n│   ├── en.yaml, ko.yaml, ja.yaml, es.yaml, pt.yaml\n├── 003/\n│   ├── en.yaml, pt.yaml, fr.yaml, ko.yaml, de.yaml, it.yaml, es.yaml, ja.yaml\n├── 004/\n│   ├── en.yaml, es.yaml, it.yaml, fr.yaml, pt.yaml, ko.yaml, ja.yaml\n├── 005/\n│   ├── en.yaml, it.yaml, de.yaml, ko.yaml, ru.yaml, tr.yaml, pl.yaml, pt.yaml, ja.yaml, fr.yaml, es.yaml\n├── 006/\n│   └── pt.yaml\n└── 008/\n    ├── en.yaml, es.yaml, it.yaml, pt.yaml\n```\n\n### registry.yaml\nÍndice mestre com: PUB sheet ID, language map (ING→en, FRA→fr, etc.), lista de todos os 39 canais.\n\n### Config por canal (ex: 003/fr.yaml)\n```yaml\naccount: '003'\nlanguage: fr\nchannel_name: C003 FRA (6) x\npub_row: 16\nsheet_scripts_id: 1H-9M1V_COUWOu9TLPLB2R41z5XMrzdh6mhXxo-XY6n8\nsheet_scripts_name: Pagina1\nsheet_tracking_id: 1fnA5QeiNDTzakQW8gtVovLnlAofMWGDfGHGmm6ZX3TE\ndrive_folder_id: 17FSjYxw3NEOuKHqA3abE0IJAN6V9u_H7\nchannel_url: https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCzfZRuRHSp6erCwzuhjywFw\nv3_config: accounts/003_wwii_photography/configs/003-fr.yaml\n```\n\n---\n\n## Fluxo Completo\n\n```\nLucca → Tobias: \"produz um vídeo\" ou \"só conta 03 hoje\"\n         |\nTobias → PM: \"escolhe o mais urgente\" ou \"produz 003 fr\"\n         |\nPM:\n  1. Lê registry.yaml (lista de canais)\n  2. Lê PUB sheet (Google Sheets API)\n  3. Filtra: PROD=SIM + scripts > 0\n  4. Calcula runway por canal (PROGRAMAR + dias até ULT PUB)\n  5. Aplica override se houver (ex: \"só conta 03\")\n  6. Ordena por menor runway\n  7. Escolhe top 1\n  8. Lê config YAML desse canal\n  9. Gera artefacto JSON (job)\n         |\nArtefacto → Video Orchestrator\n         |\nVO:\n  1. Cria directório do vídeo\n  2. Busca script (Google Sheets)\n  3. Orquestra S1→S2→...→S10\n  4. Reporta status ao Tobias/Lucca\n\n[44 more lines in file. Use offset=221 to continue.]"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774882261517}}
{"type":"message","id":"e8ff3490","parentId":"7d6a4cba","timestamp":"2026-03-30T14:51:45.477Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_9GVVJtoEqyQyRF6uGXhNctRu|fc_0047bd771936d8e20169ca8dda080c8195ae86e291c9fdbc05","name":"write","arguments":{"path":"C:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\docs\\contracts\\pm_read_pub_contract.md","content":"# PM `read_pub` Contract\n\n_Status: v1 draft based on current PM documentation. This is a contract draft for implementation, not a claim that all operational choices are fully frozen._\n\n_Last updated: 2026-03-30_\n\n---\n\n## Purpose\n\n`read_pub` is the Production Manager's deterministic ingestion layer for the canonical PUB spreadsheet.\n\nIts job is to:\n- authenticate with the canonical Google service account\n- read the `PUB` tab from the canonical spreadsheet\n- normalize the rows relevant to production prioritization\n- filter out channels that are not eligible for production\n- compute runway per eligible channel\n- return a stable, machine-consumable structure for PM decision-making\n\n`read_pub` does **not**:\n- choose the final production target on its own if an explicit direct order was given upstream\n- generate the PM -> VO job artifact\n- apply complex business overrides beyond the explicitly supported filter contract\n- mutate Sheets or Drive\n\n---\n\n## Canonical source\n\n### Spreadsheet\n- **Sheet ID**: `1XL6VhOTVVMmfGNqPyJra2T8KjfFbtJ1o16OZkytvCPc`\n- **Tab**: `PUB`\n\n### Credentials\n- **Credential model**: Google service account\n- **Canonical credential path**: `C:\\secrets\\content_factory\\google_service_account.json`\n\n### Dependencies\n- Google Sheets API must be enabled\n- The service account must have at least read access to the canonical spreadsheet\n\n---\n\n## Inputs\n\n### Required runtime inputs\n1. `credential_path`\n   - default canonical value: `C:\\secrets\\content_factory\\google_service_account.json`\n2. `sheet_id`\n   - default canonical value: `1XL6VhOTVVMmfGNqPyJra2T8KjfFbtJ1o16OZkytvCPc`\n3. `tab_name`\n   - default canonical value: `PUB`\n4. `today`\n   - ISO date or runtime-local current date used to compute runway\n\n### Optional runtime inputs\n5. `allowed_accounts`\n   - list of account IDs to restrict evaluation\n6. `allowed_languages`\n   - list of languages to restrict evaluation\n7. `pub_row_subset`\n   - optional row subset for testing/debugging\n8. `override_filter`\n   - structured upstream filter contract, if already resolved by PM/override parser\n\n---\n\n## Required columns from PUB\n\nThe current PM documentation defines these columns as the minimum required fields:\n\n| Column | Header | Meaning |\n|--------|--------|---------|\n| B | `ULT PUB` | Date of last already-scheduled publication |\n| F | `PROGRAMAR` | Videos ready but not yet uploaded/scheduled |\n| J | `PROD` | Whether production is active for the channel (`SIM` / `NÃO`) |\n| O | `SCRIPTS` | Script usage in `used/total` format |\n\n### Additional identification data\n`read_pub` must also retain enough row identity to map a row to:\n- `pub_row`\n- `account`\n- `language`\n- `channel_name`\n\nThe current contract assumes those mappings are resolved via the local account registry and/or documented row mapping already defined by PM docs.\n\n---\n\n## Eligibility rules\n\nA row is eligible for PM prioritization only if all of the following are true:\n\n1. `PROD = SIM`\n2. `scripts_remaining > 0`\n3. the row can be mapped to a valid local account/language/config entry\n4. required fields for runway calculation can be parsed successfully\n\nRows that fail any of the above must not be included in the eligible result set.\n\nThey should instead be returned in a structured `excluded_rows` or `errors` section.\n\n---\n\n## Parsing and normalization rules\n\n### `ULT PUB`\n- Expected format: date value representing the last scheduled publication date\n- Minimum v1 behavior:\n  - parse documented date format reliably\n  - normalize to ISO date in output\n- If unparsable:\n  - mark row invalid\n  - exclude from eligible set\n  - emit structured error\n\n### `PROGRAMAR`\n- Expected semantic: integer count of already-produced but not-yet-scheduled videos\n- Normalize to integer\n- If missing or invalid:\n  - mark row invalid\n  - exclude from eligible set\n  - emit structured error\n\n### `PROD`\n- Expected semantic: active production flag\n- Minimum supported positive value in v1: `SIM`\n- Any non-`SIM` value is treated as inactive\n\n### `SCRIPTS`\n- Expected format: `used/total`, e.g. `38/57`\n- Parse into:\n  - `scripts_used`\n  - `scripts_total`\n  - `scripts_remaining = scripts_total - scripts_used`\n- If malformed:\n  - mark row invalid\n  - exclude from eligible set\n  - emit structured error\n\n---\n\n## Runway calculation\n\nCanonical formula from PM documentation:\n\n```text\nrunway_days = PROGRAMAR + days_until_last_scheduled_publication\n```\n\nWhere:\n- `PROGRAMAR` = count from column F\n- `days_until_last_scheduled_publication = ULT_PUB - today`\n\n### Notes\n- Negative runway is valid and indicates urgency/deficit\n- Zero runway is valid\n- Higher runway means more content buffer\n- Lower runway means higher urgency\n\n---\n\n## Sorting / prioritization output\n\nFor the base `read_pub` contract, the output list should be sorted by:\n\n1. lowest `runway_days`\n2. lower account number as tiebreaker, based on current PM documentation\n\n### Important boundary\n`read_pub` should compute and sort.\nFinal PM decision logic that applies richer overrides may happen one layer above unless explicitly folded into this skill later.\n\n---\n\n## Output contract\n\nThe primary output should be a stable JSON-serializable structure.\n\n### Suggested top-level shape\n\n```json\n{\n  \"source\": {\n    \"sheet_id\": \"1XL6VhOTVVMmfGNqPyJra2T8KjfFbtJ1o16OZkytvCPc\",\n    \"tab_name\": \"PUB\",\n    \"read_at\": \"2026-03-30T11:00:00-03:00\"\n  },\n  \"eligible_channels\": [],\n  \"excluded_rows\": [],\n  \"errors\": []\n}\n```\n\n### Required fields for each eligible channel\n\n```json\n{\n  \"pub_row\": 16,\n  \"account\": \"003\",\n  \"language\": \"fr\",\n  \"channel_name\": \"C003 FRA\",\n  \"ult_pub_raw\": \"27/03/2026\",\n  \"ult_pub_iso\": \"2026-03-27\",\n  \"programar\": 0,\n  \"prod\": \"SIM\",\n  \"scripts_raw\": \"38/57\",\n  \"scripts_used\": 38,\n  \"scripts_total\": 57,\n  \"scripts_remaining\": 19,\n  \"runway_days\": 1,\n  \"eligible\": true,\n  \"reason\": \"PROD=SIM, scripts_remaining>0, runway=1\"\n}\n```\n\n### Required fields for excluded rows\nAt minimum:\n- `pub_row`\n- row identity if available\n- `excluded_reason`\n- `raw_values` or safe debugging fields when useful\n\n### Required fields for errors\nAt minimum:\n- `code`\n- `message`\n- `scope` (`sheet`, `row`, `auth`, `parse`, etc.)\n- `pub_row` when applicable\n\n---\n\n## Error handling\n\n### Fatal errors\nThese should fail the whole call:\n- credential file missing\n- credential file unreadable\n- authentication failure\n- spreadsheet not found\n- tab not found\n- Google API unavailable for the whole request\n\n### Row-level errors\nThese should not fail the entire call if partial read is still meaningful:\n- invalid date in `ULT PUB`\n- malformed `SCRIPTS`\n- invalid `PROGRAMAR`\n- unmapped row/account/language\n\n### Partial success rule\nIf the sheet is readable and at least one valid eligible row exists, `read_pub` may return partial success with row-level errors attached.\n\n---\n\n## Non-goals for v1\n\nThe following are intentionally outside the initial `read_pub` contract unless later promoted:\n- caching / snapshot fallback\n- write-back to Sheets\n- direct job creation\n- script locking\n- advanced override semantics in natural language\n- historical analytics / trend reporting\n\n---\n\n## Open questions to confirm later\n\nThese are not frozen by this v1 contract:\n\n1. What is the final source of truth if PUB and local YAML diverge?\n2. Should `read_pub` support cache/last-known-good snapshot on API failure?\n3. What exact upstream component resolves natural-language overrides into structured filters?\n4. What exact row/account/language mapping logic should be canonical if the sheet identity layer is ambiguous?\n5. Should inactive/malformed rows be returned with full debug payloads or only sanitized summaries?\n\n---\n\n## Recommended implementation split\n\nTo keep responsibilities clean, implementation should likely be split into:\n\n- `runtime/integrations/google_sheets.py`\n- `runtime/pm/read_pub.py`\n- `runtime/pm/pub_row_normalizer.py`\n- `runtime/pm/job_builder.py`\n- `runtime/pm/job_validator.py`\n\n`read_pub` should remain the deterministic ingestion layer, not absorb the whole PM.\n"},"partialJson":"{\"path\":\"C:\\\\Users\\\\User-OEM\\\\Desktop\\\\content-factory\\\\auto_content_factory\\\\docs\\\\contracts\\\\pm_read_pub_contract.md\",\"content\":\"# PM `read_pub` Contract\\n\\n_Status: v1 draft based on current PM documentation. This is a contract draft for implementation, not a claim that all operational choices are fully frozen._\\n\\n_Last updated: 2026-03-30_\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Purpose\\n\\n`read_pub` is the Production Manager's deterministic ingestion layer for the canonical PUB spreadsheet.\\n\\nIts job is to:\\n- authenticate with the canonical Google service account\\n- read the `PUB` tab from the canonical spreadsheet\\n- normalize the rows relevant to production prioritization\\n- filter out channels that are not eligible for production\\n- compute runway per eligible channel\\n- return a stable, machine-consumable structure for PM decision-making\\n\\n`read_pub` does **not**:\\n- choose the final production target on its own if an explicit direct order was given upstream\\n- generate the PM -> VO job artifact\\n- apply complex business overrides beyond the explicitly supported filter contract\\n- mutate Sheets or Drive\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Canonical source\\n\\n### Spreadsheet\\n- **Sheet ID**: `1XL6VhOTVVMmfGNqPyJra2T8KjfFbtJ1o16OZkytvCPc`\\n- **Tab**: `PUB`\\n\\n### Credentials\\n- **Credential model**: Google service account\\n- **Canonical credential path**: `C:\\\\secrets\\\\content_factory\\\\google_service_account.json`\\n\\n### Dependencies\\n- Google Sheets API must be enabled\\n- The service account must have at least read access to the canonical spreadsheet\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Inputs\\n\\n### Required runtime inputs\\n1. `credential_path`\\n   - default canonical value: `C:\\\\secrets\\\\content_factory\\\\google_service_account.json`\\n2. `sheet_id`\\n   - default canonical value: `1XL6VhOTVVMmfGNqPyJra2T8KjfFbtJ1o16OZkytvCPc`\\n3. `tab_name`\\n   - default canonical value: `PUB`\\n4. `today`\\n   - ISO date or runtime-local current date used to compute runway\\n\\n### Optional runtime inputs\\n5. `allowed_accounts`\\n   - list of account IDs to restrict evaluation\\n6. `allowed_languages`\\n   - list of languages to restrict evaluation\\n7. `pub_row_subset`\\n   - optional row subset for testing/debugging\\n8. `override_filter`\\n   - structured upstream filter contract, if already resolved by PM/override parser\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Required columns from PUB\\n\\nThe current PM documentation defines these columns as the minimum required fields:\\n\\n| Column | Header | Meaning |\\n|--------|--------|---------|\\n| B | `ULT PUB` | Date of last already-scheduled publication |\\n| F | `PROGRAMAR` | Videos ready but not yet uploaded/scheduled |\\n| J | `PROD` | Whether production is active for the channel (`SIM` / `NÃO`) |\\n| O | `SCRIPTS` | Script usage in `used/total` format |\\n\\n### Additional identification data\\n`read_pub` must also retain enough row identity to map a row to:\\n- `pub_row`\\n- `account`\\n- `language`\\n- `channel_name`\\n\\nThe current contract assumes those mappings are resolved via the local account registry and/or documented row mapping already defined by PM docs.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Eligibility rules\\n\\nA row is eligible for PM prioritization only if all of the following are true:\\n\\n1. `PROD = SIM`\\n2. `scripts_remaining > 0`\\n3. the row can be mapped to a valid local account/language/config entry\\n4. required fields for runway calculation can be parsed successfully\\n\\nRows that fail any of the above must not be included in the eligible result set.\\n\\nThey should instead be returned in a structured `excluded_rows` or `errors` section.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Parsing and normalization rules\\n\\n### `ULT PUB`\\n- Expected format: date value representing the last scheduled publication date\\n- Minimum v1 behavior:\\n  - parse documented date format reliably\\n  - normalize to ISO date in output\\n- If unparsable:\\n  - mark row invalid\\n  - exclude from eligible set\\n  - emit structured error\\n\\n### `PROGRAMAR`\\n- Expected semantic: integer count of already-produced but not-yet-scheduled videos\\n- Normalize to integer\\n- If missing or invalid:\\n  - mark row invalid\\n  - exclude from eligible set\\n  - emit structured error\\n\\n### `PROD`\\n- Expected semantic: active production flag\\n- Minimum supported positive value in v1: `SIM`\\n- Any non-`SIM` value is treated as inactive\\n\\n### `SCRIPTS`\\n- Expected format: `used/total`, e.g. `38/57`\\n- Parse into:\\n  - `scripts_used`\\n  - `scripts_total`\\n  - `scripts_remaining = scripts_total - scripts_used`\\n- If malformed:\\n  - mark row invalid\\n  - exclude from eligible set\\n  - emit structured error\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Runway calculation\\n\\nCanonical formula from PM documentation:\\n\\n```text\\nrunway_days = PROGRAMAR + days_until_last_scheduled_publication\\n```\\n\\nWhere:\\n- `PROGRAMAR` = count from column F\\n- `days_until_last_scheduled_publication = ULT_PUB - today`\\n\\n### Notes\\n- Negative runway is valid and indicates urgency/deficit\\n- Zero runway is valid\\n- Higher runway means more content buffer\\n- Lower runway means higher urgency\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Sorting / prioritization output\\n\\nFor the base `read_pub` contract, the output list should be sorted by:\\n\\n1. lowest `runway_days`\\n2. lower account number as tiebreaker, based on current PM documentation\\n\\n### Important boundary\\n`read_pub` should compute and sort.\\nFinal PM decision logic that applies richer overrides may happen one layer above unless explicitly folded into this skill later.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Output contract\\n\\nThe primary output should be a stable JSON-serializable structure.\\n\\n### Suggested top-level shape\\n\\n```json\\n{\\n  \\\"source\\\": {\\n    \\\"sheet_id\\\": \\\"1XL6VhOTVVMmfGNqPyJra2T8KjfFbtJ1o16OZkytvCPc\\\",\\n    \\\"tab_name\\\": \\\"PUB\\\",\\n    \\\"read_at\\\": \\\"2026-03-30T11:00:00-03:00\\\"\\n  },\\n  \\\"eligible_channels\\\": [],\\n  \\\"excluded_rows\\\": [],\\n  \\\"errors\\\": []\\n}\\n```\\n\\n### Required fields for each eligible channel\\n\\n```json\\n{\\n  \\\"pub_row\\\": 16,\\n  \\\"account\\\": \\\"003\\\",\\n  \\\"language\\\": \\\"fr\\\",\\n  \\\"channel_name\\\": \\\"C003 FRA\\\",\\n  \\\"ult_pub_raw\\\": \\\"27/03/2026\\\",\\n  \\\"ult_pub_iso\\\": \\\"2026-03-27\\\",\\n  \\\"programar\\\": 0,\\n  \\\"prod\\\": \\\"SIM\\\",\\n  \\\"scripts_raw\\\": \\\"38/57\\\",\\n  \\\"scripts_used\\\": 38,\\n  \\\"scripts_total\\\": 57,\\n  \\\"scripts_remaining\\\": 19,\\n  \\\"runway_days\\\": 1,\\n  \\\"eligible\\\": true,\\n  \\\"reason\\\": \\\"PROD=SIM, scripts_remaining>0, runway=1\\\"\\n}\\n```\\n\\n### Required fields for excluded rows\\nAt minimum:\\n- `pub_row`\\n- row identity if available\\n- `excluded_reason`\\n- `raw_values` or safe debugging fields when useful\\n\\n### Required fields for errors\\nAt minimum:\\n- `code`\\n- `message`\\n- `scope` (`sheet`, `row`, `auth`, `parse`, etc.)\\n- `pub_row` when applicable\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Error handling\\n\\n### Fatal errors\\nThese should fail the whole call:\\n- credential file missing\\n- credential file unreadable\\n- authentication failure\\n- spreadsheet not found\\n- tab not found\\n- Google API unavailable for the whole request\\n\\n### Row-level errors\\nThese should not fail the entire call if partial read is still meaningful:\\n- invalid date in `ULT PUB`\\n- malformed `SCRIPTS`\\n- invalid `PROGRAMAR`\\n- unmapped row/account/language\\n\\n### Partial success rule\\nIf the sheet is readable and at least one valid eligible row exists, `read_pub` may return partial success with row-level errors attached.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Non-goals for v1\\n\\nThe following are intentionally outside the initial `read_pub` contract unless later promoted:\\n- caching / snapshot fallback\\n- write-back to Sheets\\n- direct job creation\\n- script locking\\n- advanced override semantics in natural language\\n- historical analytics / trend reporting\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Open questions to confirm later\\n\\nThese are not frozen by this v1 contract:\\n\\n1. What is the final source of truth if PUB and local YAML diverge?\\n2. Should `read_pub` support cache/last-known-good snapshot on API failure?\\n3. What exact upstream component resolves natural-language overrides into structured filters?\\n4. What exact row/account/language mapping logic should be canonical if the sheet identity layer is ambiguous?\\n5. Should inactive/malformed rows be returned with full debug payloads or only sanitized summaries?\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Recommended implementation split\\n\\nTo keep responsibilities clean, implementation should likely be split into:\\n\\n- `runtime/integrations/google_sheets.py`\\n- `runtime/pm/read_pub.py`\\n- `runtime/pm/pub_row_normalizer.py`\\n- `runtime/pm/job_builder.py`\\n- `runtime/pm/job_validator.py`\\n\\n`read_pub` should remain the deterministic ingestion layer, not absorb the whole PM.\\n\"}"}],"api":"openai-codex-responses","provider":"openai-codex","model":"gpt-5.4","usage":{"input":2479,"output":2205,"cacheRead":114560,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":119244,"cost":{"input":0.006197500000000001,"output":0.033075,"cacheRead":0.02864,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.067912