openai-codex","model":"gpt-5.4","usage":{"input":95738,"output":203,"cacheRead":57856,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":153797,"cost":{"input":0.23934500000000003,"output":0.003045,"cacheRead":0.014464,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.256854}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774896973239,"responseId":"resp_0047bd771936d8e20169cac74ef504819580785f2feeb35903"}}
{"type":"message","id":"e1e3f1c9","parentId":"ab9c4fec","timestamp":"2026-03-30T18:56:24.536Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_TQfXFRDM7iyMQ2GwBUbKywim|fc_0047bd771936d8e20169cac757e8088195909d0b958aa10224","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"\"\"\"\r\nTranscription Validator for Content Factory V3.\r\n\r\nValidates TTS output by transcribing via WhisperX and comparing\r\nwith the original text. Detects when AllTalk \"eats\" words or\r\nproduces completely wrong pronunciations.\r\n\r\nPart of Step 3.8b in the V3 Scene-First architecture.\r\n\"\"\"\r\n\r\nimport re\r\nfrom dataclasses import dataclass, field\r\nfrom difflib import SequenceMatcher\r\nfrom typing import List, Optional, Tuple\r\n\r\nfrom loguru import logger\r\n\r\n\r\n@dataclass\r\nclass ValidationResult:\r\n    \"\"\"Result of transcription validation.\"\"\"\r\n\r\n    is_valid: bool\r\n    match_ratio: float  # 0.0 to 1.0\r\n    original_text: str\r\n    transcribed_text: str\r\n    missing_words: List[str] = field(default_factory=list)\r\n    extra_words: List[str] = field(default_factory=list)\r\n    word_error_rate: float = 0.0\r\n    details: str = \"\"\r\n    # Thresholds used for this validation\r\n    language: str = \"\"\r\n    threshold_used: float = 0.0\r\n    exclude_words_used: List[str] = field(default_factory=list)\r\n    filtered_extra_count: int = 0  # Extra words after filtering\r\n\r\n\r\nclass TranscriptionValidator:\r\n    \"\"\"\r\n    Validates TTS audio by comparing original text with WhisperX transcription.\r\n\r\n    The validator checks:\r\n    1. Word coverage - were all words pronounced?\r\n    2. Word accuracy - were words pronounced correctly?\r\n    3. Overall similarity - Levenshtein-based match ratio\r\n\r\n    Thresholds are language-aware since some languages (ja, ko, ar) have\r\n    different transcription characteristics.\r\n    \"\"\"\r\n\r\n    # Minimum match ratio to consider audio valid\r\n    DEFAULT_THRESHOLD = 0.85\r\n\r\n    # Language-specific thresholds - calibrated from false positive analysis (Jan 2026)\r\n    # Key finding: match_ratio alone has 56-92% false positive rate due to numbers/proper nouns\r\n    # Updated Feb 2026: Added exclude_words for EN to handle number words (threshold stays 60%)\r\n    LANGUAGE_THRESHOLDS = {\r\n        # Asian languages - character-based, transcription varies\r\n        \"ja\": 0.75,\r\n        \"ko\": 0.75,\r\n        # Other challenging languages\r\n        \"ar\": 0.80,  # Arabic - diacritics variation\r\n        \"ru\": 0.82,  # Russian - stress variations\r\n        \"pl\": 0.82,  # Polish - consonant clusters\r\n        # Western European - calibrated from 6-language analysis\r\n        \"de\": 0.65,  # German: compound numbers (einundzwanzig) cause divergence\r\n        \"en\": 0.60,  # English: 60% threshold, number words filtered via exclude_words\r\n        \"pt\": 0.75,  # Portuguese: contracted articles (\"do\" = \"de o\")\r\n        \"es\": 0.70,  # Spanish: contractions (del, al)\r\n        \"it\": 0.70,  # Italian: contracted articles + \"zero\" bug\r\n        \"fr\": 0.65,  # French: contractions + \"cents\" bug\r\n        \"nl\": 0.70,  # Dutch: similar to German\r\n        \"tr\": 0.75,  # Turkish: agglutinative, but less compound issues\r\n        \"default\": 0.85\r\n    }\r\n\r\n    # Language-specific configuration for advanced validation\r\n    LANGUAGE_CONFIG = {\r\n        \"it\": {\r\n            \"exclude_words\": [\"zero\", \"virgola\"],  # TTS Polish bug: speaks \"zero\" for 0\r\n        },\r\n        \"fr\": {\r\n            \"exclude_words\": [\"cents\", \"zéro\"],    # TTS Polish bug: speaks \"cents\" for numbers\r\n        },\r\n        \"de\": {\r\n            \"ignore_patterns\": [r\"\\d+\"],           # Compound numbers\r\n        },\r\n        \"en\": {\r\n            \"ignore_patterns\": [r\"'s$\", r\"\\d+\"],   # Possessives/contractions + digits\r\n            # Number words that TTS Polish generates but WhisperX may transcribe differently\r\n            \"exclude_words\": [\r\n                # Basic numbers (WhisperX often transcribes as digits)\r\n                \"one\", \"two\", \"three\", \"four\", \"five\", \"six\", \"seven\", \"eight\", \"nine\", \"ten\",\r\n                \"eleven\", \"twelve\", \"thirteen\", \"fourteen\", \"fifteen\", \"sixteen\", \"seventeen\",\r\n                \"eighteen\", \"nineteen\", \"twenty\", \"thirty\", \"forty\", \"fifty\", \"sixty\",\r\n                \"seventy\", \"eighty\", \"ninety\", \"hundred\", \"thousand\", \"million\",\r\n                # Compound numbers (TTS Polish joins them: \"twentytwo\")\r\n                \"twentyone\", \"twentytwo\", \"twentythree\", \"twentyfour\", \"twentyfive\",\r\n                \"twentysix\", \"twentyseven\", \"twentyeight\", \"twentynine\",\r\n                # Date-related Latin words (Anno Domini, etc.)\r\n                \"anno\", \"domini\", \"ad\", \"bc\", \"ce\", \"bce\",\r\n                # Ordinals\r\n                \"first\", \"second\", \"third\", \"fourth\", \"fifth\", \"sixth\", \"seventh\",\r\n                \"eighth\", \"ninth\", \"tenth\", \"eleventh\", \"twelfth\",\r\n            ],\r\n        },\r\n    }\r\n\r\n    # Common transcription variations that should not fail validation\r\n    ACCEPTABLE_VARIATIONS = {\r\n        \"en\": [\r\n            (\"okay\", \"ok\"),\r\n            (\"cannot\", \"can't\"),\r\n            (\"will not\", \"won't\"),\r\n        ],\r\n        \"pt\": [\r\n            (\"você\", \"voce\"),\r\n            (\"é\", \"eh\"),\r\n            (\"não\", \"nao\"),\r\n        ],\r\n        \"es\": [\r\n            (\"está\", \"esta\"),\r\n            (\"qué\", \"que\"),\r\n        ],\r\n        \"fr\": [\r\n            (\"c'est\", \"cest\"),\r\n            (\"n'est\", \"nest\"),\r\n        ],\r\n        \"de\": [\r\n            (\"ß\", \"ss\"),\r\n        ],\r\n    }\r\n\r\n    def __init__(\r\n        self,\r\n        language: str = \"en\",\r\n        threshold: Optional[float] = None,\r\n        strict_mode: bool = False\r\n    ):\r\n        \"\"\"\r\n        Initialize validator.\r\n\r\n        Args:\r\n            language: ISO language code\r\n            threshold: Custom match threshold (0.0-1.0), None uses defaults\r\n            strict_mode: If True, uses stricter matching rules\r\n        \"\"\"\r\n        self.language = language.lower()\r\n        self.strict_mode = strict_mode\r\n\r\n        if threshold is not None:\r\n            self.threshold = threshold\r\n        else:\r\n            self.threshold = self.LANGUAGE_THRESHOLDS.get(\r\n                self.language,\r\n                self.LANGUAGE_THRESHOLDS[\"default\"]\r\n            )\r\n\r\n        # Get language-specific config\r\n        self.lang_config = self.LANGUAGE_CONFIG.get(self.language, {})\r\n\r\n        # Log initialization with threshold details\r\n        exclude_words = self.lang_config.get(\"exclude_words\", [])\r\n        ignore_patterns = self.lang_config.get(\"ignore_patterns\", [])\r\n        logger.info(\r\n            f\"TranscriptionValidator initialized: lang={language}, \"\r\n            f\"match_ratio>={self.threshold}, strict={strict_mode}\"\r\n        )\r\n        if exclude_words:\r\n            logger.info(f\"  exclude_words: {exclude_words}\")\r\n        if ignore_patterns:\r\n            logger.info(f\"  ignore_patterns: {ignore_patterns}\")\r\n\r\n    def validate(\r\n        self,\r\n        original_text: str,\r\n        transcribed_text: str\r\n    ) -> ValidationResult:\r\n        \"\"\"\r\n        Validate transcribed text against original.\r\n\r\n        Args:\r\n            original_text: The text that was sent to TTS\r\n            transcribed_text: The text from WhisperX transcription\r\n\r\n        Returns:\r\n            ValidationResult with match details\r\n        \"\"\"\r\n        # Normalize both texts\r\n        original_normalized = self._normalize_text(original_text)\r\n        transcribed_normalized = self._normalize_text(transcribed_text)\r\n\r\n        # Get word lists\r\n        original_words = original_normalized.split()\r\n        transcribed_words = transcribed_normalized.split()\r\n\r\n        # Strip numeric tokens (exclude_words + digit patterns) from both texts\r\n        # before calculating match_ratio, so \"four hundred thousand\" vs \"400,000\"\r\n        # doesn't tank the ratio\r\n        original_clean = self._strip_numeric_tokens(original_words)\r\n        transcribed_clean = self._strip_numeric_tokens(transcribed_words)\r\n\r\n        # Calculate match ratio on cleaned texts\r\n        # CRITICAL: autojunk=False prevents SequenceMatcher from treating\r\n        # frequent characters (spaces, 'e', 't', etc.) as junk.\r\n        # With autojunk=True (default), strings of ~200+ chars have most\r\n        # letters treated as junk, yielding absurdly low ratios (~20%)\r\n        # for nearly identical texts.\r\n        matcher = SequenceMatcher(\r\n            None,\r\n            \" \".join(original_clean),\r\n            \" \".join(transcribed_clean),\r\n            autojunk=False,\r\n        )\r\n        match_ratio = matcher.ratio()\r\n\r\n        # Calculate word-level metrics\r\n        missing_words, extra_words = self._find_word_differences(\r\n            original_words,\r\n            transcribed_words\r\n        )\r\n\r\n        # Filter BOTH missing and extra words using language-specific rules\r\n        filtered_extra_words = self._filter_ignored_words(extra_words)\r\n        filtered_missing_words = self._filter_ignored_words(missing_words)\r\n\r\n        # Calculate Word Error Rate (WER) on cleaned word lists\r\n        wer = self._calculate_wer(original_clean, transcribed_clean)\r\n\r\n        # Determine if valid - use filtered counts\r\n        is_valid = match_ratio >= self.threshold\r\n\r\n        # Additional check: if extra words exceed threshold, flag as invalid\r\n        # This catches TTS repetitions/hallucinations that match_ratio misses\r\n        regen_extra_words = self.lang_config.get(\"regen_extra_words\", 5)\r\n        if len(filtered_extra_words) >= regen_extra_words:\r\n            is_valid = False\r\n\r\n        # In strict mode, also check that critical words are not missing\r\n        if self.strict_mode and is_valid:\r\n            # Check if more than 10% of non-numeric words are missing\r\n            if len(filtered_missing_words) > len(original_clean) * 0.1:\r\n                is_valid = False\r\n\r\n        # Build result - use filtered lists for reporting\r\n        total_filtered = (len(extra_words) - len(filtered_extra_words)) + \\\r\n                         (len(missing_words) - len(filtered_missing_words))\r\n        result = ValidationResult(\r\n            is_valid=is_valid,\r\n            match_ratio=match_ratio,\r\n            original_text=original_text,\r\n            transcribed_text=transcribed_text,\r\n            missing_words=filtered_missing_words,\r\n            extra_words=filtered_extra_words,\r\n            word_error_rate=wer,\r\n            details=self._build_details(\r\n                match_ratio,\r\n                wer,\r\n                filtered_missing_words,\r\n                filtered_extra_words,\r\n                is_valid\r\n            ),\r\n            # Thresholds used for auditing\r\n            language=self.language,\r\n            threshold_used=self.threshold,\r\n            exclude_words_used=self.lang_config.get(\"exclude_words\", []),\r\n            filtered_extra_count=total_filtered,\r\n        )\r\n\r\n        # Log result with language and threshold info\r\n        status = \"PASS\" if is_valid else \"FAIL\"\r\n        logger.info(\r\n            f\"Transcription validation [{self.language.upper()}]: {status} \"\r\n            f\"(ratio={match_ratio:.2%} >= {self.threshold:.0%}, \"\r\n            f\"missing={len(filtered_missing_words)}, extra={len(filtered_extra_words)}\"\r\n            f\"{f', filtered={total_filtered}' if total_filtered > 0 else ''})\"\r\n        )\r\n\r\n        return result\r\n\r\n    def _normalize_text(self, text: str) -> str:\r\n        \"\"\"\r\n        Normalize text for comparison.\r\n\r\n        Removes punctuation, converts to lowercase, normalizes whitespace.\r\n        Applies language-specific normalization (accents, etc).\r\n        \"\"\"\r\n        if not text:\r\n            return \"\"\r\n\r\n        # Convert to lowercase\r\n        text = text.lower()\r\n\r\n        # Apply language-specific variations\r\n        variations = self.ACCEPTABLE_VARIATIONS.get(self.language, [])\r\n        for original, replacement in variations:\r\n            text = text.replace(original.lower(), replacement.lower())\r\n\r\n        # Replace hyphens with spaces BEFORE stripping punctuation,\r\n        # so \"forty-eight\" becomes \"forty eight\" (two separate tokens\r\n        # that _strip_numeric_tokens can match), not \"fortyeight\".\r\n        text = text.replace('-', ' ')\r\n\r\n        # Remove punctuation (keep letters, numbers, spaces)\r\n        # For CJK languages, keep the characters\r\n        if self.language in (\"ja\", \"ko\", \"zh\"):\r\n            # Keep CJK characters + alphanumeric\r\n            text = re.sub(r'[^\\w\\s\\u4e00-\\u9fff\\u3040-\\u309f\\u30a0-\\u30ff\\uac00-\\ud7af]', '', text)\r\n        else:\r\n            # Standard: keep alphanumeric + common accented chars\r\n            text = re.sub(r'[^\\w\\s\\u00c0-\\u017f]', '', text)\r\n\r\n        # Normalize whitespace\r\n        text = ' '.join(text.split())\r\n\r\n        return text\r\n\r\n    def _find_word_differences(\r\n        self,\r\n        original_words: List[str],\r\n        transcribed_words: List[str]\r\n    ) -> Tuple[List[str], List[str]]:\r\n        \"\"\"\r\n        Find words that are missing or extra in transcription.\r\n\r\n        Returns:\r\n            Tuple of (missing_words, extra_words)\r\n        \"\"\"\r\n        original_set = set(original_words)\r\n        transcribed_set = set(transcribed_words)\r\n\r\n        # Words in original but not in transcription\r\n        missing = list(original_set - transcribed_set)\r\n\r\n        # Words in transcription but not in original\r\n        extra = list(transcribed_set - original_set)\r\n\r\n        return missing, extra\r\n\r\n    def _filter_ignored_words(self, words: List[str]) -> List[str]:\r\n        \"\"\"\r\n        Filter out words that should be ignored based on language config.\r\n\r\n        This filters out known TTS Polish bugs (e.g., \"zero\" in Italian,\r\n        \"cents\" in French) and words matching ignore patterns.\r\n\r\n        Args:\r\n            words: List of words to filter\r\n\r\n        Returns:\r\n            Filtered list with ignored words removed\r\n        \"\"\"\r\n        exclude_words = set(self.lang_config.get(\"exclude_words\", []))\r\n        ignore_patterns = self.lang_config.get(\"ignore_patterns\", [])\r\n\r\n        filtered = []\r\n        for word in words:\r\n            word_lower = word.lower()\r\n\r\n            # Skip explicitly excluded words (TTS Polish bugs)\r\n            if word_lower in exclude_words:\r\n                continue\r\n\r\n            # Skip words matching ignore patterns\r\n            should_ignore = False\r\n            for pattern in ignore_patterns:\r\n                if re.match(pattern, word_lower):\r\n                    should_ignore = True\r\n                    break\r\n\r\n            if not should_ignore:\r\n                filtered.append(word)\r\n\r\n        return filtered\r\n\r\n    def _strip_numeric_tokens(self, words: List[str]) -> List[str]:\r\n        \"\"\"\r\n        Remove number-related tokens from word list before comparison.\r\n\r\n        Strips both digit sequences (400000) and number words (hundred, thousand)\r\n        so that TTS-polished text and WhisperX transcription compare fairly.\r\n        \"\"\"\r\n        exclude_words = set(self.lang_config.get(\"exclude_words\", []))\r\n        ignore_patterns = self.lang_config.get(\"ignore_patterns\", [])\r\n\r\n        result = []\r\n        for word in words:\r\n            word_lower = word.lower()\r\n            if word_lower in exclude_words:\r\n                continue\r\n            skip = False\r\n            for pattern in ignore_patterns:\r\n                if re.match(pattern, word_lower):\r\n                    skip = True\r\n                    break\r\n            if not skip:\r\n                result.append(word)\r\n        return result\r\n\r\n    def _calculate_wer(\r\n        self,\r\n        reference: List[str],\r\n        hypothesis: List[str]\r\n    ) -> float:\r\n        \"\"\"\r\n        Calculate Word Error Rate using Levenshtein distance.\r\n\r\n        WER = (S + D + I) / N\r\n        where S = substitutions, D = deletions, I = insertions, N = reference length\r\n        \"\"\"\r\n        if not reference:\r\n            return 1.0 if hypothesis else 0.0\r\n\r\n        # Build distance matrix\r\n        d = [[0] * (len(hypothesis) + 1) for _ in range(len(reference) + 1)]\r\n\r\n        for i in range(len(reference) + 1):\r\n            d[i][0] = i\r\n        for j in range(len(hypothesis) + 1):\r\n            d[0][j] = j\r\n\r\n        for i in range(1, len(reference) + 1):\r\n            for j in range(1, len(hypothesis) + 1):\r\n                if reference[i - 1] == hypothesis[j - 1]:\r\n                    d[i][j] = d[i - 1][j - 1]\r\n                else:\r\n                    substitution = d[i - 1][j - 1] + 1\r\n                    insertion = d[i][j - 1] + 1\r\n                    deletion = d[i - 1][j] + 1\r\n                    d[i][j] = min(substitution, insertion, deletion)\r\n\r\n        return d[len(reference)][len(hypothesis)] / len(reference)\r\n\r\n    def _build_details(\r\n        self,\r\n        match_ratio: float,\r\n        wer: float,\r\n        missing_words: List[str],\r\n        extra_words: List[str],\r\n        is_valid: bool\r\n    ) -> str:\r\n        \"\"\"Build human-readable details string.\"\"\"\r\n        parts = [\r\n            f\"Match ratio: {match_ratio:.1%} (threshold: {self.threshold:.1%})\",\r\n            f\"Word Error Rate: {wer:.1%}\",\r\n        ]\r\n\r\n        if missing_words:\r\n            parts.append(f\"Missing words ({len(missing_words)}): {', '.join(missing_words[:5])}\")\r\n            if len(missing_words) > 5:\r\n                parts[-1] += f\"... and {len(missing_words) - 5} more\"\r\n\r\n        if extra_words:\r\n            parts.append(f\"Extra words ({len(extra_words)}): {', '.join(extra_words[:5])}\")\r\n            if len(extra_words) > 5:\r\n                parts[-1] += f\"... and {len(extra_words) - 5} more\"\r\n\r\n        parts.append(f\"Result: {'PASSED' if is_valid else 'FAILED'}\")\r\n\r\n        return \" | \".join(parts)\r\n\r\n\r\ndef validate_tts_output(\r\n    original_text: str,\r\n    transcribed_text: str,\r\n    language: str = \"en\",\r\n    threshold: Optional[float] = None\r\n) -> ValidationResult:\r\n    \"\"\"\r\n    Convenience function to validate TTS output.\r\n\r\n    Args:\r\n        original_text: Text sent to TTS\r\n        transcribed_text: WhisperX transcription\r\n        language: Language code\r\n        threshold: Optional custom threshold\r\n\r\n    Returns:\r\n        ValidationResult\r\n    \"\"\"\r\n    validator = TranscriptionValidator(\r\n        language=language,\r\n        threshold=threshold\r\n    )\r\n    return validator.validate(original_text, transcribed_text)\r\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774896984401}}
{"type":"message","id":"6fba6c94","parentId":"e1e3f1c9","timestamp":"2026-03-30T18:56:24.662Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_1jkX6PzLGXgzF8Z5BN1REkKy|fc_0047bd771936d8e20169cac757e81481959f9bdc59a3c40063","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"                        \"qg_result\": qg_result,\n                        \"transcribed_text\": transcribed_text,\n                        \"match_ratio\": validation_result.match_ratio,\n                    }\n\n                if validation_result.is_valid:\n                    logger.success(\n                        f\"    WhisperX PASSED: {validation_result.match_ratio:.1%} match\"\n                    )\n                    break\n                else:\n                    logger.warning(\n                        f\"    WhisperX FAILED (attempt {pipeline_attempt + 1}/{self.MAX_PIPELINE_RETRIES}): \"\n                        f\"{validation_result.match_ratio:.1%} match\"\n                    )\n                    final_audio = None\n                    current_wav = self._regenerate_clip_sync(polished)\n                    raw_path.write_bytes(current_wav)  # overwrite on disk\n\n            # Best effort fallback\n            used_best_effort = False\n            if final_audio is None:\n                if best_attempt[\"audio\"] is not None:\n                    logger.warning(\n                        f\"    Scene {scene_num}: using BEST EFFORT \"\n                        f\"(match={best_attempt['match_ratio']:.1%})\"\n                    )\n                    final_audio = best_attempt[\"audio\"]\n                    transcription = best_attempt[\"transcription\"]\n                    validation_result = best_attempt[\"validation_result\"]\n                    qg_result = best_attempt[\"qg_result\"]\n                    transcribed_text = best_attempt[\"transcribed_text\"]\n                    used_best_effort = True\n                else:\n                    raise RuntimeError(\n                        f\"Scene {scene_num}: audio generation completely failed\"\n                    )\n\n            # Save final clip as MP3 and remove raw WAV\n            final_audio.export(str(output_path), format=\"mp3\")\n            raw_path.unlink(missing_ok=True)\n            duration_ms = len(final_audio)\n\n            # Build clip metadata (same structure as sequential path)\n            clip_meta = {\n                \"scene_number\": scene_num,\n                \"clip_name\": clip_name,\n                \"path\": str(output_path),\n                \"duration_ms\": duration_ms,\n                \"original_text\": scene_text,\n                \"polished_text\": polished,\n                \"quality_gate\": {\n                    \"status\": qg_result.status.value if qg_result else \"skipped\",\n                    \"mos\": qg_result.metrics.mos if qg_result else None,\n                },\n                \"whisperx\": {\n                    \"transcribed_text\": transcribed_text,\n                    \"match_ratio\": validation_result.match_ratio if validation_result else None,\n                    \"is_valid\": validation_result.is_valid if validation_result else None,\n                },\n                \"used_best_effort\": used_best_effort,\n                \"word_timestamps\": [],\n            }\n\n            # Extract word timestamps from transcription\n            if transcription and hasattr(transcription, \"words\"):\n                clip_meta[\"word_timestamps\"] = [\n                    {\"word\": w.word, \"start\": w.start, \"end\": w.end}\n                    for w in transcription.words\n                    if hasattr(w, \"word\")\n                ]\n\n            clips_metadata.append(clip_meta)\n\n            # Save per-clip WhisperX JSON (parity with V1 sequential path)\n            if transcription is not None:\n                whisperx_data = {\n                    \"scene_number\": scene_num,\n                    \"polished_text\": polished,\n                    \"total_duration\": getattr(transcription, \"total_duration\", None),\n                    \"word_count\": getattr(transcription, \"word_count\", None),\n                    \"full_transcript\": getattr(transcription, \"full_transcript\", transcribed_text),\n                    \"segments\": [],\n                }\n                if hasattr(transcription, \"segments\"):\n                    for seg in transcription.segments:\n                        seg_data = {\n                            \"start\": seg.start,\n                            \"end\": seg.end,\n                            \"text\": seg.text,\n                            \"words\": [\n                                {\"word\": w.word, \"start\": w.start, \"end\": w.end}\n                                for w in (seg.words or [])\n                                if hasattr(w, \"word\")\n                            ],\n                        }\n                        whisperx_data[\"segments\"].append(seg_data)\n                whisperx_path = self.clips_dir / f\"{clip_name}_whisperx.json\"\n                whisperx_path.write_text(\n                    json.dumps(whisperx_data, indent=2, ensure_ascii=False),\n                    encoding=\"utf-8\",\n                )\n\n            # Write validation entry progressively\n            validation_entry = {\n                \"scene_number\": scene_num,\n                \"polished_text\": polished,\n                \"transcribed_text\": transcribed_text or \"\",\n                \"match_ratio\": validation_result.match_ratio if validation_result else None,\n                \"passed_first_attempt\": (\n                    validation_result.is_valid if validation_result else None\n                ) and pipeline_attempt == 0,\n                \"attempts\": pipeline_attempt + 1,\n                \"regenerated\": pipeline_attempt > 0 or used_best_effort,\n                \"used_best_effort\": used_best_effort,\n                \"duration_ms\": duration_ms,\n                \"mos_score\": qg_result.metrics.mos if qg_result else None,\n            }\n            validation_entries.append(validation_entry)\n            try:\n\n[271 more lines in file. Use offset=1270 to continue.]"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774896984537}}
{"type":"message","id":"4112d0d2","parentId":"6fba6c94","timestamp":"2026-03-30T18:56:24.784Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_cYa7QXU8UBJT9aQaDyaouDcM|fc_0047bd771936d8e20169cac757e81c8195a16d076c6168ec4b","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# ============================================================\r\n\r\ndef _align_words_to_timestamps(\r\n    original_text: str,\r\n    word_timestamps: List[List],\r\n) -> Dict[str, int]:\r\n    \"\"\"Align original script words with WhisperX timestamps by position.\r\n\r\n    Uses SequenceMatcher to map original_text words to WhisperX word_timestamps,\r\n    handling cases where WhisperX mishears words (e.g., \"911\" -> \"1091\").\r\n    The alignment transfers timestamps from WhisperX words to the corresponding\r\n    original words based on their position in the sequence.\r\n\r\n    Args:\r\n        original_text: The original script text for this scene.\r\n        word_timestamps: Compact format [[\"word\", start_frame, end_frame], ...]\r\n\r\n    Returns:\r\n        Dict mapping normalized original word -> start_frame.\r\n        Only first occurrence of each word is stored.\r\n    \"\"\"\r\n    if not original_text or not word_timestamps:\r\n        return {}\r\n\r\n    original_words = original_text.split()\r\n    if not original_words:\r\n        return {}\r\n\r\n    whisperx_words = [w[0] for w in word_timestamps]\r\n\r\n    # Normalize for alignment (lowercase, strip punctuation)\r\n    def _norm(w: str) -> str:\r\n        return re.sub(r'[^\\w]', '', w.lower())\r\n\r\n    orig_norm = [_norm(w) for w in original_words]\r\n    wsx_norm = [_norm(w) for w in whisperx_words]\r\n\r\n    matcher = SequenceMatcher(None, orig_norm, wsx_norm)\r\n    word_to_frame: Dict[str, int] = {}\r\n\r\n    for tag, i1, i2, j1, j2 in matcher.get_opcodes():\r\n        if tag == \"equal\":\r\n            # Perfect match — transfer timestamps directly\r\n            for i, j in zip(range(i1, i2), range(j1, j2)):\r\n                key = _norm(original_words[i])\r\n                if key and key not in word_to_frame:\r\n                    word_to_frame[key] = word_timestamps[j][1]\r\n        elif tag == \"replace\":\r\n            # Positional transfer (e.g., \"911\" -> \"1091\")\r\n            for i, j in zip(range(i1, i2), range(j1, j2)):\r\n                key = _norm(original_words[i])\r\n                if key and key not in word_to_frame:\r\n                    word_to_frame[key] = word_timestamps[j][1]\r\n        # \"insert\" and \"delete\" ops: no direct mapping possible\r\n\r\n    return word_to_frame\r\n\r\n\r\n# ============================================================\r\n# Trigger frame resolution (from word_timestamps)\r\n# ============================================================\r\n\r\ndef resolve_trigger_frames(\r\n    plan_entries: List[Dict[str, Any]],\r\n    planner_batches: List[Dict[str, Any]],\r\n) -> List[Dict[str, Any]]:\r\n    \"\"\"Resolve trigger_word -> trigger_frame using word_timestamps from planner batches.\r\n\r\n    Args:\r\n        plan_entries: Lettering plan entries with scene, trigger_word\r\n        planner_batches: List of planner batch dicts with scenes containing word_timestamps\r\n\r\n    Returns:\r\n        Updated plan entries with trigger_frame and scene timing added.\r\n    \"\"\"\r\n    # Build lookup: scene_index -> {word_timestamps, start_frame, end_frame, aligned_map}\r\n    scene_data: Dict[int, Dict] = {}\r\n    for batch in planner_batches:\r\n        for scene in batch.get(\"scenes\", []):\r\n            idx = scene.get(\"scene_index\")\r\n            if idx is None:\r\n                continue\r\n            timing = scene.get(\"timing\", {})\r\n            audio = scene.get(\"audio\", {})\r\n            wts = audio.get(\"word_timestamps\", [])\r\n            scene_data[idx] = {\r\n                \"start_frame\": timing.get(\"start_frame\", 0),\r\n                \"end_frame\": timing.get(\"end_frame\", 0),\r\n                \"word_timestamps\": wts,\r\n                \"aligned_map\": _align_words_to_timestamps(\r\n                    audio.get(\"original_text\", \"\"), wts\r\n                ),\r\n            }\r\n\r\n    resolved = []\r\n    for entry in plan_entries:\r\n        entry = dict(entry)  # copy\r\n        scene_idx = entry.get(\"scene\")\r\n        trigger_word = entry.get(\"trigger_word\", \"\")\r\n        sd = scene_data.get(scene_idx)\r\n\r\n        if sd:\r\n            entry[\"scene_start_frame\"] = sd[\"start_frame\"]\r\n            entry[\"scene_end_frame\"] = sd[\"end_frame\"]\r\n\r\n            # Try aligned map first (handles WhisperX mishearing via positional alignment)\r\n            trigger_clean = re.sub(r'[^\\w]', '', trigger_word.lower())\r\n            aligned_frame = sd[\"aligned_map\"].get(trigger_clean) if trigger_clean else None\r\n\r\n            if aligned_frame is not None:\r\n                entry[\"trigger_frame\"] = aligned_frame\r\n            else:\r\n                # Fallback: 3-pass matching on raw WhisperX words\r\n                frame = _find_trigger_frame(sd[\"word_timestamps\"], trigger_word)\r\n                if frame is not None:\r\n                    entry[\"trigger_frame\"] = frame\r\n                else:\r\n                    # Last resort: scene first-third fallback (better than dropping)\r\n                    scene_start = sd[\"start_frame\"]\r\n                    scene_dur = sd[\"end_frame\"] - scene_start\r\n\n[86 more lines in file. Use offset=3060 to continue.]"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774896984664}}
{"type":"message","id":"caf09509","parentId":"4112d0d2","timestamp":"2026-03-30T18:56:24.911Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_86cVl9TgL3lmKLLvDgzQlJH8|fc_0047bd771936d8e20169cac757e8248195b89fc4fcedb05c68","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"\r\n    def generate_voiceover(\r\n        self,\r\n        script_data: ScriptData,\r\n        path_config: PathConfig,\r\n        formatted_name: str,\r\n        language: str = \"es\",\r\n        speaker_wav: Optional[str] = None,\r\n    ) -> Path:\r\n        \"\"\"\r\n        Generate voiceover from script and save to file.\r\n\r\n        Args:\r\n            script_data: Script data to convert to speech\r\n            path_config: Path configuration\r\n            formatted_name: Formatted video name\r\n            language: Language code\r\n            speaker_wav: Path to speaker voice sample (folder or file)\r\n\r\n        Returns:\r\n            Path to saved audio file\r\n        \"\"\"\r\n        try:\r\n            logger.info(f\"Generating voiceover for: {script_data.title}\")\r\n\r\n            # Use script.script directly (already processed by orchestrator)\r\n            # The orchestrator applies:\r\n            # 1. clean_script() - removes line breaks, special quotes\r\n            # 2. apply_language_specific_formatting() - normalizes times, BC/AD, units, roman numerals\r\n            #    AND applies PT/IT semicolon formatting (. -> ; with 2 spaces for pacing)\r\n            #\r\n            # IMPORTANT: Do NOT use script_data.cleaned_script property!\r\n            # That property applies re.sub(r\"\\s+\", \" \", ...) which destroys the\r\n            # 2 spaces after semicolons that are critical for PT/IT TTS pacing.\r\n            processed_script = script_data.script\r\n\r\n            # Sanitize for TTS (removes URLs, emails, special symbols)\r\n            tts_text = ScriptProcessor.sanitize_for_tts(processed_script)\r\n\r\n            # Get output path\r\n            output_path = path_config.get_voiceover_path(formatted_name)\r\n\r\n            # Language-specific chunk sizes\r\n            # CJK languages (Japanese, Korean) use fewer characters because each character = 1 syllable\r\n            # AllTalk has a 95 char limit for Korean, so we use 80 to be safe\r\n            CHUNK_SIZES = {\r\n                \"ja\": 80,   # Japanese - each character is a syllable\r\n                \"ko\": 80,   # Korean - AllTalk limit is 95, use 80 for safety\r\n                \"ar\": 150,  # Arabic - slightly shorter due to complex script\r\n                \"default\": 200  # Latin/Cyrillic languages\r\n            }\r\n            max_chunk_size = CHUNK_SIZES.get(language, CHUNK_SIZES[\"default\"])\r\n\r\n            # Use manual chunking for all languages (improved quality)\r\n            logger.info(f\"Using manual chunking strategy ({max_chunk_size} chars for {language.upper()}, 350ms pauses)\")\r\n\r\n            chunks = self._split_text_into_chunks(tts_text, max_chunk_size=max_chunk_size)\r\n\r\n            # Save original chunks for comparison log\r\n            original_chunks = chunks.copy()\r\n\r\n            # TTS Polish Agent - polish chunks with LLM before sending to TTS\r\n            # This fixes: abbreviations, numbers, gender agreement, unnatural phrasing\r\n            try:\r\n                from .tts_polish_agent import TTSPolishAgent\r\n                polish_agent = TTSPolishAgent(language=language, enable_evaluator=False)\r\n                original_count = len(chunks)\r\n                chunks = polish_agent.polish_chunks(chunks)\r\n                logger.success(f\"TTS Polish Agent: {len(chunks)} chunks polished successfully\")\r\n            except Exception as e:\r\n                logger.error(f\"TTS Polish Agent failed: {e}\")\r\n                raise  # Fail the video if polish fails (per user requirement)\r\n\r\n            # Save BEFORE vs AFTER comparison log for validation\r\n            comparison_log_path = path_config.get_voiceover_path(formatted_name).parent / f\"{formatted_name}_polish_comparison.txt\"\r\n            self._save_polish_comparison_log(\r\n                original_chunks=original_chunks,\r\n                polished_chunks=chunks,\r\n                language=language,\r\n                title=script_data.title,\r\n                output_path=comparison_log_path\r\n            )\r\n\r\n            # Remove trailing periods for non-PT/IT languages\r\n            # This prevents AllTalk from literally speaking \"punto/punkt/point\" etc.\r\n            # IMPORTANT: This runs AFTER the Polish Agent\r\n            chunks = [self._remove_trailing_period_for_tts(c, language) for c in chunks]\r\n\r\n            logger.info(f\"Created {len(chunks)} chunks for processing\")\r\n\r\n            # Save chunks to file for validation\r\n            chunks_log_path = output_path.parent / f\"{formatted_name}_chunks_log.txt\"\r\n            with chunks_log_path.open(\"w\", encoding=\"utf-8\") as f:\r\n                f.write(\"=\" * 80 + \"\\n\")\r\n                f.write(f\"CHUNKS SENT TO XTTS - {language.upper()}\\n\")\r\n                f.write(f\"Video: {script_data.title}\\n\")\r\n                f.write(\"=\" * 80 + \"\\n\\n\")\r\n\r\n                for i, chunk in enumerate(chunks, 1):\r\n                    f.write(f\"CHUNK {i} ({len(chunk)} caracteres)\\n\")\r\n                    f.write(\"-\" * 80 + \"\\n\")\r\n                    f.write(f\"{chunk}\\n\")\r\n                    f.write(\"\\n\" + \"=\" * 80 + \"\\n\\n\")\r\n\r\n            logger.success(f\"📄 Chunks log saved to: {chunks_log_path}\")\r\n\r\n            # Generate audio for each chunk\r\n            audio_segments = []\r\n            for i, chunk in enumerate(chunks, 1):\r\n                logger.info(f\"Generating audio for chunk {i}/{len(chunks)} ({len(chunk)} chars)\")\r\n\r\n                audio_data = self.xtts.generate_audio(\r\n                    text=chunk,\r\n                    language=language,\r\n                    speaker_wav=speaker_wav,\r\n                )\r\n\r\n                # Convert bytes to AudioSegment\r\n                audio_segment = AudioSegment.from_file(io.BytesIO(audio_data), format=\"wav\")\r\n                audio_segments.append(audio_segment)\r\n\r\n            # Concatenate with 350ms pauses and 20ms crossfade\r\n            logger.info(f\"Concatenating {len(audio_segments)} audio segments with 350ms pauses + 20ms crossfade\")\r\n            silence = AudioSegment.silent(duration=350)\r\n\r\n            final_audio = audio_segments[0]\r\n            for segment in audio_segments[1:]:\r\n                # Add silence with crossfade (eliminates clicks/pops at junctions)\r\n                final_audio = final_audio.append(silence, crossfade=20)\r\n                # Add segment with crossfade (smooth transition)\r\n                final_audio = final_audio.append(segment, crossfade=20)\r\n\r\n            # Export raw audio (before trimming)\r\n            output_path_raw = output_path.parent / f\"{output_path.stem}_raw{output_path.suffix}\"\r\n            final_audio.export(str(output_path_raw), format=\"mp3\", bitrate=\"192k\")\r\n            logger.info(f\"Raw voiceover saved: {output_path_raw.name}\")\r\n\r\n            # Trim silences (NEW - Step 3.5)\r\n            logger.info(f\"Trimming abnormal pauses (>2s with pydub, buffers: 150ms+50ms)...\")\r\n\r\n            trim_result = self.silence_trimmer.process_audio_pydub(\r\n                input_path=output_path_raw,\r\n                output_path=output_path,\r\n                dry_run=False\r\n            )\r\n\r\n            # Log trim results\r\n            if trim_result.success:\r\n                if trim_result.pauses_trimmed > 0:\r\n                    logger.success(\r\n\n[294 more lines in file. Use offset=280 to continue.]"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774896984784}}
{"type":"message","id":"f41ab284","parentId":"caf09509","timestamp":"2026-03-30T18:57:06.090Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"[[reply_to_current]] Boa. Fui mais fundo agora e já dá para fechar uma leitura bem mais concreta do **S2 real**, do **V3 actual**, e de como isso deveria virar **S2 com agentes OpenClaw**.\n\nVou organizar por blocos.\n\n---\n\n# 1. Ratio / validação no V3 actual\nO módulo central é:\n- `shared/processors/transcription_validator.py`\n\n## O que ele faz\nEle compara:\n- `original_text`\n- `transcribed_text` do WhisperX\n\ne produz:\n- `match_ratio`\n- `missing_words`\n- `extra_words`\n- `word_error_rate`\n- `is_valid`\n- `details`\n\n---\n\n## Como calcula\nNão é uma heurística burra.\n\n### Faz:\n- normalização do texto\n- remove pontuação\n- aplica variações aceitáveis por idioma\n- filtra palavras problemáticas por idioma\n- usa `SequenceMatcher(..., autojunk=False)` para `match_ratio`\n- calcula WER também\n\n### E ainda faz:\n- `exclude_words`\n- `ignore_patterns`\n- thresholds por idioma\n\nOu seja:\n## a validação do V3 está muito mais madura do que “WhisperX bateu / não bateu”\n\n---\n\n## Thresholds por idioma\nIsto é muito importante para o S2 novo.\n\nO V3 actual já tem thresholds específicos:\n\n- `en`: **0.60**\n- `fr`: **0.65**\n- `de`: **0.65**\n- `es`: **0.70**\n- `it`: **0.70**\n- `pt`: **0.75**\n- `ja`: **0.75**\n- `ko`: **0.75**\n- `ar`: **0.80**\n- `ru`: **0.82**\n- `pl`: **0.82**\n- `default`: **0.85**\n\n### Isto muda a conversa\nO S2 novo **não deveria usar threshold único**.\nDeveria herdar esta lógica do V3 ou uma adaptação directa dela.\n\n---\n\n## Config específica por idioma\nAlém do threshold, o V3 também já tem:\n- `exclude_words`\n- `ignore_patterns`\n- `acceptable_variations`\n\nExemplo:\n- EN ignora vários number words / digits\n- FR e IT têm palavras específicas ligadas a bugs do TTS polish\n- DE ignora padrões numéricos\n\nOu seja:\n## o `audio_transcriber` sozinho não basta\nprecisamos mesmo de um:\n### `transcription_validator` / `ratio_validator`\ncomo skill Python determinística do S2\n\n---\n\n# 2. O que o `parallel_tts.py` revela sobre o shape real do output\nO `shared/processors/parallel_tts.py` mostra algo muito útil sobre o que o V3 já considera output bom por cena.\n\nPara cada clip/cena, ele monta metadata tipo:\n\n- `scene_number`\n- `clip_name`\n- `path`\n- `duration_ms`\n- `original_text`\n- `polished_text`\n- `quality_gate`\n- `whisperx.transcribed_text`\n- `whisperx.match_ratio`\n- `whisperx.is_valid`\n- `used_best_effort`\n- `word_timestamps`\n\nE ainda salva um JSON por clip com:\n- `segments`\n- `words`\n- `full_transcript`\n- `total_duration`\n\n## Isto é ouro para o S2 novo\nPorque responde bem ao “que artefactos devemos criar”.\n\nO V3 já nos mostra um shape útil e testado.\n\n---\n\n# 3. Word timestamps / alignment no V3\nAqui há uma descoberta importante:\n\n## O WhisperX bruto existe\nmas o V3 também já tem:\n### alinhamento por `SequenceMatcher`\npara corrigir mishearing do WhisperX\n\nAchei isso em:\n- `shared/processors/lettering_tsx_generator.py`\n- e também em partes do `bloco2v2`\n\nA função `_align_words_to_timestamps(...)` faz basicamente:\n- recebe `original_text`\n- recebe `word_timestamps` do WhisperX\n- usa `SequenceMatcher`\n- transfere timestamps por posição mesmo quando WhisperX erra a palavra\n\nExemplo documentado:\n- `\"911\"` → `\"1091\"`\n\nOu seja:\n## a tua intuição e a review estavam certas:\no S2 novo **não devia parar em WhisperX cru**\nele devia ter um:\n### `timestamp_aligner`\n\n---\n\n# 4. O que isto implica para o desenho do S2\nCom esta ronda, eu diria que o desenho do S2 já está praticamente fechado.\n\n## O S2 novo deveria ter estes componentes:\n\n### 1. `tts_generator`\n- usa Gemini TTS\n- respeita KMS\n- voice vem do YAML\n- gera 1 clip por cena\n\n### 2. `audio_transcriber`\n- usa WhisperX local\n- transcreve 1 clip por cena\n\n### 3. `transcription_validator`\n- Python determinístico\n- reaproveita lógica do V3\n- thresholds por idioma\n- missing/extra/WER/match ratio\n\n### 4. `audio_validator`\n- operador LLM opcional\n- só entra quando o ratio está baixo/ambíguo\n- julgamento qualitativo de borderline\n\n### 5. `timestamp_aligner`\n- pega original text + word timestamps WhisperX\n- corrige alinhamento por posição\n- gera word timestamps melhores\n\n### 6. `bible_updater`\n- actualiza `scene_bible.json`\n- preenche áudio/timing por cena\n\n---\n\n# 5. Sobre chamadas paralelas\nAgora consigo te dar uma posição mais firme.\n\n## TTS\n### Sim, paralelismo controlado faz sentido\nPorque:\n- é rede/API\n- KMS já controla pool/disponibilidade\n- uma key por chamada\n- dá para limitar com cap\n\n### Regra que eu recomendaria\n- `TTS_CONCURRENCY_CAP` no supervisor\n- provavelmente por máquina\n- algo conservador no começo\n\n---\n\n## WhisperX\n### Eu manteria sequencial ou serializado\nPorque:\n- é GPU local\n- serviço único\n- já é naturalmente mais pesado\n- o ganho de paralelismo aqui tende a vir com caos/VRAM contention\n\n---\n\n## Validação/alignment/update\n### Determinístico e barato\nIsso pode correr por cena depois da transcrição, mas eu ainda manteria o pipeline por cena razoavelmente disciplinado:\n- TTS paralelo com cap\n- transcrição/validação/alignment num segundo estágio mais controlado\n\n---\n\n# 6. Como o V3 actual ficaria no S2 com agentes OpenClaw\nAgora dá para responder isso de forma mais precisa.\n\n## Não faria tudo como agente OpenClaw\nEsse é o ponto central.\n\n### Com agentes OpenClaw só quando faz sentido\nPorque o S2 tem muita coisa que é:\n- infra Python\n- serviço local\n- integração técnica\n- deterministic processing\n\nEssas partes **não deviam virar “agentes conversacionais”**.\n\n---\n\n## Minha proposta concreta\n\n### Camada A — runtime Python real\nEstas peças devem ser código do sistema:\n\n- `tts_generator.py`\n- `audio_transcriber.py`\n- `transcription_validator.py`\n- `timestamp_aligner.py`\n- `bible_updater.py`\n- talvez `whisperx_controller.py`\n\n### Camada B — supervisor do setor\n- `s2_start.py`\n\n### Camada C — operador/subagente OpenClaw opcional\nApenas:\n- `audio_validator`\n\nPorque esse sim é julgamento semântico/qualitativo quando o determinístico não basta.\n\n---\n\n# 7. Como eu traduziria o V3 para a arquitectura nova\n\n## V3 actual\n- `GeminiTTSService`\n- `WhisperXService`\n- `TranscriptionValidator`\n- alignment espalhado em lettering/visual layer\n- metadata por clip\n- KMS via client\n- paralelismo em `parallel_tts.py`\n\n## S2 novo ideal\n### subir isso para uma arquitectura mais limpa:\n\n#### `runtime/s2/tts_generator.py`\nadapta/reaproveita `GeminiTTSService`\n\n#### `runtime/s2/audio_transcriber.py`\nadapta/reaproveita `WhisperXService`\n\n#### `runtime/s2/transcription_validator.py`\nporta a lógica do validator do V3\n\n#### `runtime/s2/timestamp_aligner.py`\nextrai/limpa a lógica de alignment hoje espalhada\n\n#### `runtime/s2/bible_updater.py`\natualiza a `scene_bible`\n\n#### `runtime/s2/s2_start.py`\ncoordena tudo\n\n#### `audio_validator` (OpenClaw)\nsó para casos borderline\n\n---\n\n# 8. O que eu considero praticamente decidido agora\n## Fechado\n- voz vem do YAML\n- Gemini TTS deve reaproveitar substrate real do V3\n- KMS continua central para acquire/report/cooldown/disponibilidade\n- TTS service ainda trata policy específica da chamada\n- thresholds são por idioma\n- S2 precisa de `timestamp_aligner`\n- `bible_updater` deve ser Python determinístico\n- TTS pode ter paralelismo com cap\n- WhisperX deve ser controlado/serializado\n\n## Quase fechado\n- shape dos outputs por cena deve se inspirar no metadata do `parallel_tts.py`\n- `audio_validator` deve ser opcional, não caminho principal\n\n---\n\n# 9. Minha recomendação do próximo passo\nAgora sim eu acho que já dá para fazer o que interessa:\n\n## escrever o briefing super completo do S2\ncom:\n- Gemini TTS + KMS\n- voice from YAML\n- WhisperX local start/stop/transcribe\n- threshold por idioma\n- `timestamp_aligner`\n- `bible_updater`\n- checkpoints\n- paralelismo controlado\n\nSe quiseres, no próximo passo eu já te entrego esse **briefing super completo do S2**.","textSignature":"{\"v\":1,\"id\":\"msg_0047bd771936d8e20169cac75d14648195b8eedf98405e572a\",\"phase\":\"final_answer\"}"}],"api":"openai-codex-responses","provider":"openai-codex","model":"gpt-5.4","usage":{"input":56632,"output":2090,"cacheRead":79360,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":138082,"cost":{"input":0.14158,"output":0.03135,"cacheRead":0.01984,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.19277000000000002}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1774896985566,"responseId":"resp_0047bd771936d8e20169cac75b2d5c819585c709ed852140fd"}}
{"type":"message","id":"f5bb471e","parentId":"f41ab284","timestamp":"2026-03-30T18:57:28.077Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Pre-compaction memory flush. Store durable memories only in memory/2026-03-30.md (create memory/ if needed). Treat workspace bootstrap/reference files such as MEMORY.md, SOUL.md, TOOLS.md, and AGENTS.md as read-only during this flush; never overwrite, replace, or edit them. If memory/2026-03-30.md already exists, APPEND new content only and do not overwrite existing entries. Do NOT create timestamped variant files (e.g., 2026-03-30-HHMM.md); always use the canonical 2026-03-30.md filename. If nothing to store, reply with NO_REPLY.\nCurrent time: Monday, March 30th, 2026 — 15:57 (America/Sao_Paulo) / 2026-03-30 18:57 UTC"}],"timestamp":1774897047999}}
{"type":"message","id":"5365eb20","parentId":"f5bb471e","timestamp":"2026-03-30T18:58:07.625Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_4tNaiuJ0CvZiGMrhOxtM9AhD|fc_0047bd771936d8e20169cac79e81a88195b6d9bebe838da235","name":"write","arguments":{"path":"C:\\Users\\User-OEM\\.openclaw\\workspace\\memory\\2026-03-30.md","content":"## Durable memory flush — 2026-03-30\n\n- Lucca accidentally reset the session; we reconstructed the relevant thread by reading the 29 Mar review materials and repo docs instead of guessing.\n- Important correction: previous memory had overemphasized Telegram/watchdog context. The real active thread on 30 Mar was implementation planning/execution for the Content Factory editing department, especially PM -> VO -> S1 -> S2 architecture and Claude Code coordination.\n- PM (Production Manager) architecture was materially advanced today:\n  - We created canonical docs:\n    - `auto_content_factory/docs/contracts/pm_read_pub_contract.md`\n    - `auto_content_factory/docs/contracts/pm_override_contract.md`\n  - We aligned PM mirror/docs around these contracts.\n  - We standardized the Google service-account credential path for OpenClaw/runtime use as:\n    - `C:\\secrets\\content_factory\\google_service_account.json`\n  - Lucca confirmed the reused V3 service account has valid access to Sheets/Drive.\n- Claude Code successfully implemented PM substrate v1 and then the override layer. Real outcomes:\n  - PM can read the real PUB sheet, rank channels, support `auto_select`, `filtered_select`, `direct_select`, build canonical jobs, and validate them.\n  - Real observed PUB state during testing:\n    - 38 eligible channels\n    - all with negative runway\n    - `C001 PT` excluded because scripts are exhausted\n    - `C004 FRA` was top urgency at runway `-17`\n  - Durable principle confirmed: PM must treat PUB as operational truth, not strategic sovereignty; Tobias remains the upstream strategic layer.\n- We intentionally formalized the PM operating modes as durable architecture:\n  - `auto_select`\n  - `filtered_select`\n  - `direct_select`\n  with authority order `direct_select > filtered_select > auto_select`.\n  Critical rules:\n  - `filtered_select` must not silently fall back to unrestricted auto mode.\n  - `direct_select` must not silently choose another channel if the requested target is invalid.\n- Claude Code successfully implemented VO minimal bootstrap on top of real PM jobs:\n  - PM -> VO handoff works end-to-end.\n  - VO creates runs under the canonical production root:\n    - `C:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\production\\{account}_{language}\\{job_id}\\`\n  - Policy chosen: if the run directory already exists, fail explicitly with `run_already_exists` (safe, deterministic, no silent merging).\n  - VO bootstrap writes real artefacts like `job.json`, `run_metadata.json`, `checkpoints/vo_init.json`.\n- We investigated V3 script fetch/lock behavior before designing the next VO step. Durable findings from `content_factory_v3`:\n  - Script selection rule is simple and important: pick the first row with `Status = \"to do\"`.\n  - Lock is applied by immediately updating sheet status to `processing`.\n  - Legacy sheet columns in V3 are roughly:\n    - `E = Status`\n    - `F = Processing_Started`\n    - `G = Processing_Completed`\n    - `H = Account_Used`\n  - This V3 semantics should be reused for the new VO rather than inventing a new lock system early.\n- Claude Code then implemented `script_fetch_and_lock` successfully with real integrations:\n  - PM -> VO -> script fetch & lock works end-to-end with real data.\n  - Example real result:\n    - `direct_select 004/fr`\n    - script row 6 selected: `Les Enfants de la Creuse`\n    - real sheet lock applied (`Status -> processing`)\n    - local script artefacts written under `production/.../inputs/script/`\n    - run ended at `next_step = ready_for_s1`\n- S1 (Pre-Production) work advanced substantially. Important architectural findings:\n  - Canonical source for S1 is `docs/branches/01_PRE_PRODUCTION.md`; the workspace mirror is not reliable enough as source of truth.\n  - Canonical naming for this sector should be `b1_`, not `s1_`.\n  - S1 is already well-defined in docs as:\n    - `scene_director`\n    - `screenplay_validator`\n    - `tts_polish`\n    - `polish_validator`\n    - `scene_bible_builder`\n    - checkpoints by step\n  - `scene_bible.json` is the core output and should live at the run root as a living document.\n- Claude Code implemented S1 and passed tests, but there is an important durable nuance:\n  - The deterministic/runtime pieces are solid and reusable:\n    - validators\n    - scene_bible builder\n    - schema validator\n    - checkpoint writer\n    - supervisor base\n  - But the LLM operator steps (`scene_director`, `tts_polish`) were implemented as direct Python OpenAI API calls (`gpt-4.1-mini`) instead of real OpenClaw operators using the planned runtime (GPT-5.4 mini OAuth / Qwen local).\n  - Therefore Tobias’ judgment is:\n    - treat S1 as a **functional prototype accepted for pipeline validation**\n    - not as final production-runtime architecture\n  - We should preserve this distinction explicitly and not let the temporary Python direct-call mode become accidental production standard.\n- Lucca agreed with the Tobias recommendation to accept S1 as a prototype-functional slice and move on to S2 while keeping the runtime-architecture debt explicit.\n- S2 investigation produced durable architecture conclusions:\n  - Canonical doc: `docs/branches/02_AUDIO.md`, but review shows the sector is split between two versions.\n  - The more mature conceptual direction is:\n    - `tts_generator`\n    - `audio_transcriber`\n    - `transcription/ratio validator`\n    - `audio_validator` (LLM only for borderline cases)\n    - `timestamp_aligner`\n    - `bible_updater`\n  - This is superior to the older `timing_extractor`-only model.\n- Durable V3 findings for S2 / audio:\n  - Gemini TTS in V3 is already implemented as a serious reusable substrate (`shared/services/gemini_tts_service.py`).\n  - The TTS request is driven by:\n    - text\n    - explicit `language_code`\n    - explicit `voice_name`\n  - Voice choice should come exclusively from the channel YAML config in the new S2; no extra heuristic speaker selection.\n  - KMS already manages key acquisition/reporting/cooldown/availability centrally; the TTS client should not reinvent that logic.\n  - Client-side Gemini TTS code still appropriately handles call-specific behavior like hard timeouts, empty responses, content-block inference, and PCM->WAV packing.\n- Durable V3 findings for WhisperX / validation / alignment:\n  - WhisperX is managed as a local service that can be started/stopped/health-checked; Lucca says it stays off by default to avoid consuming GPU.\n  - V3 has a mature `TranscriptionValidator` with language-specific thresholds, ignore patterns, exclude words, WER, and match ratio logic.\n  - Example thresholds in V3 are language-specific and should strongly influence the new S2 (not a single universal threshold):\n    - `en 0.60`, `fr 0.65`, `de 0.65`, `es 0.70`, `it 0.70`, `pt 0.75`, `ja 0.75`, `ko 0.75`, `ar 0.80`, `ru 0.82`, `pl 0.82`, default `0.85`.\n  - V3 also already contains useful positional alignment logic using `SequenceMatcher` to transfer WhisperX timestamps back onto original script words when WhisperX mishears tokens (e.g. `911 -> 1091`). This is strong evidence that the new S2 should explicitly include `timestamp_aligner`, not just raw timestamp extraction.\n- Durable architecture recommendation for S2 going forward:\n  - TTS should allow controlled parallelism with a supervisor-level `TTS_CONCURRENCY_CAP`.\n  - WhisperX should remain serialized / carefully controlled (GPU/local-service bound).\n  - The likely OpenClaw-era layering for S2 is:\n    - Python/runtime skills for:\n      - `tts_generator`\n      - `audio_transcriber`\n      - `transcription_validator`\n      - `timestamp_aligner`\n      - `bible_updater`\n    - one OpenClaw LLM operator only where it adds semantic judgment:\n      - `audio_validator`\n    - an `SM-S2` supervisor coordinating retries, parallelism, and checkpoints.\n"},"partialJson":"{\"path\":\"C:\\\\Users\\\\User-OEM\\\\.openclaw\\\\workspace\\\\memory\\\\2026-03-30.md\",\"content\":\"## Durable memory flush — 2026-03-30\\n\\n- Lucca accidentally reset the session; we reconstructed the relevant thread by reading the 29 Mar review materials and repo docs instead of guessing.\\n- Important correction: previous memory had overemphasized Telegram/watchdog context. The real active thread on 30 Mar was implementation planning/execution for the Content Factory editing department, especially PM -> VO -> S1 -> S2 architecture and Claude Code coordination.\\n- PM (Production Manager) architecture was materially advanced today:\\n  - We created canonical docs:\\n    - `auto_content_factory/docs/contracts/pm_read_pub_contract.md`\\n    - `auto_content_factory/docs/contracts/pm_override_contract.md`\\n  - We aligned PM mirror/docs around these contracts.\\n  - We standardized the Google service-account credential path for OpenClaw/runtime use as:\\n    - `C:\\\\secrets\\\\content_factory\\\\google_service_account.json`\\n  - Lucca confirmed the reused V3 service account has valid access to Sheets/Drive.\\n- Claude Code successfully implemented PM substrate v1 and then the override layer. Real outcomes:\\n  - PM can read the real PUB sheet, rank channels, support `auto_select`, `filtered_select`, `direct_select`, build canonical jobs, and validate them.\\n  - Real observed PUB state during testing:\\n    - 38 eligible channels\\n    - all with negative runway\\n    - `C001 PT` excluded because scripts are exhausted\\n    - `C004 FRA` was top urgency at runway `-17`\\n  - Durable principle confirmed: PM must treat PUB as operational truth, not strategic sovereignty; Tobias remains the upstream strategic layer.\\n- We intentionally formalized the PM operating modes as durable architecture:\\n  - `auto_select`\\n  - `filtered_select`\\n  - `direct_select`\\n  with authority order `direct_select > filtered_select > auto_select`.\\n  Critical rules:\\n  - `filtered_select` must not silently fall back to unrestricted auto mode.\\n  - `direct_select` must not silently choose another channel if the requested target is invalid.\\n- Claude Code successfully implemented VO minimal bootstrap on top of real PM jobs:\\n  - PM -> VO handoff works end-to-end.\\n  - VO creates runs under the canonical production root:\\n    - `C:\\\\Users\\\\User-OEM\\\\Desktop\\\\content-factory\\\\auto_content_factory\\\\production\\\\{account}_{language}\\\\{job_id}\\\\`\\n  - Policy chosen: if the run directory already exists, fail explicitly with `run_already_exists` (safe, deterministic, no silent merging).\\n  - VO bootstrap writes real artefacts like `job.json`, `run_metadata.json`, `checkpoints/vo_init.json`.\\n- We investigated V3 script fetch/lock behavior before designing the next VO step. Durable findings from `content_factory_v3`:\\n  - Script selection rule is simple and important: pick the first row with `Status = \\\"to do\\\"`.\\n  - Lock is applied by immediately updating sheet status to `processing`.\\n  - Legacy sheet columns in V3 are roughly:\\n    - `E = Status`\\n    - `F = Processing_Started`\\n    - `G = Processing_Completed`\\n    - `H = Account_Used`\\n  - This V3 semantics should be reused for the new VO rather than inventing a new lock system early.\\n- Claude Code then implemented `script_fetch_and_lock` successfully with real integrations:\\n  - PM -> VO -> script fetch & lock works end-to-end with real data.\\n  - Example real result:\\n    - `direct_select 004/fr`\\n    - script row 6 selected: `Les Enfants de la Creuse`\\n    - real sheet lock applied (`Status -> processing`)\\n    - local script artefacts written under `production/.../inputs/script/`\\n    - run ended at `next_step = ready_for_s1`\\n- S1 (Pre-Production) work advanced substantially. Important architectural findings:\\n  - Canonical source for S1 is `docs/branches/01_PRE_PRODUCTION.md`; the workspace mirror is not reliable enough as source of truth.\\n  - Canonical naming for this sector should be `b1_`, not `s1_`.\\n  - S1 is already well-defined in docs as:\\n    - `scene_director`\\n    - `screenplay_validator`\\n    - `tts_polish`\\n    - `polish_validator`\\n    - `scene_bible_builder`\\n    - checkpoints by step\\n  - `scene_bible.json` is the core output and should live at the run root as a living document.\\n- Claude Code implemented S1 and passed tests, but there is an important durable nuance:\\n  - The deterministic/runtime pieces are solid and reusable:\\n    - validators\\n    - scene_bible builder\\n    - schema validator\\n    - checkpoint writer\\n    - supervisor base\\n  - But the LLM operator steps (`scene_director`, `tts_polish`) were implemented as direct Python OpenAI API calls (`gpt-4.1-mini`) instead of real OpenClaw operators using the planned runtime (GPT-5.4 mini OAuth / Qwen local).\\n  - Therefore Tobias’ judgment is:\\n    - treat S1 as a **functional prototype accepted for pipeline validation**\\n    - not as final production-runtime architecture\\n  - We should preserve this distinction explicitly and not let the temporary Python direct-call mode become accidental production standard.\\n- Lucca agreed with the Tobias recommendation to accept S1 as a prototype-functional slice and move on to S2 while keeping the runtime-architecture debt explicit.\\n- S2 investigation produced durable architecture conclusions:\\n  - Canonical doc: `docs/branches/02_AUDIO.md`, but review shows the sector is split between two versions.\\n  - The more mature conceptual direction is:\\n    - `tts_generator`\\n    - `audio_transcriber`\\n    - `transcription/ratio validator`\\n    - `audio_validator` (LLM only for borderline cases)\\n    - `timestamp_aligner`\\n    - `bible_updater`\\n  - This is superior to the older `timing_extractor`-only model.\\n- Durable V3 findings for S2 / audio:\\n  - Gemini TTS in V3 is already implemented as a serious reusable substrate (`shared/services/gemini_tts_service.py`).\\n  - The TTS request is driven by:\\n    - text\\n    - explicit `language_code`\\n    - explicit `voice_name`\\n  - Voice choice should come exclusively from the channel YAML config in the new S2; no extra heuristic speaker selection.\\n  - KMS already manages key acquisition/reporting/cooldown/availability centrally; the TTS client should not reinvent that logic.\\n  - Client-side Gemini TTS code still appropriately handles call-specific behavior like hard timeouts, empty responses, content-block inference, and PCM->WAV packing.\\n- Durable V3 findings for WhisperX / validation / alignment:\\n  - WhisperX is managed as a local service that can be started/stopped/health-checked; Lucca says it stays off by default to avoid consuming GPU.\\n  - V3 has a mature `TranscriptionValidator` with language-specific thresholds, ignore patterns, exclude words, WER, and match ratio logic.\\n  - Example thresholds in V3 are language-specific and should strongly influence the new S2 (not a single universal threshold):\\n    - `en 0.60`, `fr 0.65`, `de 0.65`, `es 0.70`, `it 0.70`, `pt 0.75`, `ja 0.75`, `ko 0.75`, `ar 0.80`, `ru 0.82`, `pl 0.82`, default `0.85`.\\n  - V3 also already contains useful positional alignment logic using `SequenceMatcher` to transfer WhisperX timestamps back onto original script words when WhisperX mishears tokens (e.g. `911 -> 1091`). This is strong evidence that the new S2 should explicitly include `timestamp_aligner`, not just raw timestamp extraction.\\n- Durable architecture recommendation for S2 going forward:\\n  - TTS should allow controlled parallelism with a supervisor-level `TTS_CONCURRENCY_CAP`.\\n  - WhisperX should remain serialized / carefully controlled (GPU/local-service bound).\\n  - The likely OpenClaw-era layering for S2 is:\\n    - Python/runtime skills for:\\n      - `tts_generator`\\n      - `audio_transcriber`\\n      - `transcription_validator`\\n      - `timestamp_aligner`\\n      - `bible_updater`\\n    - one OpenClaw LLM operator only where it adds semantic judgment:\\n      - `audio_validator`\\n    - an `SM-S2` supervisor coordinating retries, parallelism, and checkpoints.\\n\"}"}],"api":"openai-codex-responses","provider":"openai-codex","model":"gpt-5.4","usage":{"input":139527,"output":1947,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":141474,"cost":{"input":0.3488175,"output":0.029205000000000002,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.3780225}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774897049222,"responseId":"resp_0047bd771936d8e20169cac79ace9c81959998103180be0e91"}}
